commit_message:
Added ext2 into extend_fs method in fuel_agent

Without this change it is impossible to extend
ext2 file systems which we use for /boot.

Change-Id: Icd6a3866a754b32cf0f1aa5f129674c8dfb0e0e4
Implements: blueprint image-based-provisioning

commit_message:
Enable pypi jobs for Murano projects

openstackci was added as a maintainer and owner of murano,
murano-dashboard and murano-agent.

Change-Id: I9b41ff131f30c6b095b5924a3e7a2f03c69290fc

[{'created': '2014-10-13 13:53:30.000000000', 'message': 'Sync latest code and use oslo.i18n

Modules from oslo-incubator already switched to use graduated
libraries (oslo.i18n, oslo.serialization and oslo.utils), so we
should sync latest code and remove outdated modules (gettextutils,
importutils, strutils).

Since oslo-incubator uses oslo.i18n, we require to add this library to
novaclient dependencies. This action can be more useful, if novaclient is
switch to use oslo.i18n too.

Latest commit in oslo-incubator:
    21985931a95981eabf1030ead60ae4d210bcd9c0

Change-Id: I15d36ac5a2bb88b332ffa38d29488b75c55a20a9

commit_message:
Port to use oslo.i18n

Module gettextutils from oslo-incubator was graduated to separate
library (oslo.i18n) and removed from repository, so we should use
new library.

Change-Id: I15d36ac5a2bb88b332ffa38d29488b75c55a20a9

commit_message:
Fix display name change during backup restore

Currently the display name and description of the target volume
is changed to that in the backup meta-data during backup restore.
This can confuse the end-user, especially in the case of restore
to an existing volume. This patch removes display name and display
description from the list of fields to be copied from the backup
meta-data to update the volume.

Change-Id: I21a0505352ddc8db801f4820d575399a4771b259
Closes-Bug: #1376194

commit_message:
Reduced lvm metadata size to (actual size - 8M)

The reason for that is to make sure that
there will be enough space for creating logical volumes.
Default lvm extension size is 4M. Nailgun volume
manager does not care of it and if physical volume size
is 4M * N + 3M and lvm metadata size is 4M * L then only
4M * (N-L) + 3M of space will be available for
creating logical extensions. So only 4M * (N-L) of space
will be available for logical volumes, while nailgun
volume manager might reguire 4M * (N-L) + 3M
logical volume. Besides, parted aligns partitions
according to its own algorithm and actual partition might
be a bit smaller than integer number of mebibytes.

Implements: blueprint image-based-provisioning
Change-Id: I14e5e8e37a52685a67a99fece630b368e6064c76

commit_message:
Wiping out md and lvm devices before partitioning

This change is intended to wipe out md and lvm
metadata which could remain on a disk. We do it
in 3 steps
1) we wipe out all md and lvm devices
2) we put 1M of zeros at the beginning of every new partition
3) we again wipe out all md and lvm devices

For details see comments in fuel_agent/fuel_agent/manager.py

Implements: blueprint image-based-provisioning
Change-Id: I55f18bd22f5609da18e33f1b238176c3bb95d327

How about I assert a list of known JOB_NAME values in tripleo-ci, so at least if it changes we would fail fast and not silently continue?'}, {'account_id': 1, 'date': '2014-10-13 16:05:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I'm not asserting that every individual configuration flag needs to be set in the project_config repo.  However, I am saying that the way to determine what a job does is by setting configuration flags in the project_config repo.  You don't have to list individual parameters (like USE_FOO=1 USE_BAR=0), in fact, I would prefer you didn't because that's just wasting review time.  Rather, use parameters that say "this job should test the X configuration" and then check for that in tripleo-ci.  Just never use the JOB_NAME to do that.'}, {'account_id': 1926, 'date': '2014-10-16 09:38:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2

commit_message:
Revert "Set tripleo ci control variables based on job name"

This reverts commit 9fdca6e28a435012d1be354d8547ec74f2338b16.

Changing behavior based on JOB_NAME is extremely unsafe and
should not be done.  Instead, set variables in the JJB
templates in config that describe what the job should do, and
then in this repo, enable settings accordingly.

Change-Id: Ia225600fce261fcf7999e71aed7887579b7571c0

commit_message:
Isolate Flavors API from Scheduler

As part of blueprint isolate-scheduler-db , we need to change how filters
get/check if host passes or not by only looking at HostState. Here we change
how TypeFilter is looking if there are not already other same instances with
the same instance_type instead of querying DB for instances.

Implements blueprint isolate-scheduler-db

Change-Id: Ib9fca6210c51f86731d9af35583318c51c6f4534

commit_message:
Isolate Instances API from Scheduler

As part of blueprint isolate-scheduler-db , we need to change how filters
get/check if host passes or not by only looking at HostState. Here, we change
how SameHostFilter and DifferentHostFilter are checking which instances the
host has, by updating HostState thanks to ResourceTracker instead of calling
Instances API from the filters.

Implements blueprint isolate-scheduler-db

commit_message:
SAML-related protocols must be named 'saml2'

Due to a current limitation in SAML auth plugins in the
python-keystoneclient library, protocols must be named 'saml2'.
This patch documents the limitation.

Change-Id: I0d9862db2f41209343c7e2f5a76876e9019cef59
Partial-Bug: 1380779

Remove unused variables

Work in progress. Working through in in a structured order
to tidy up the code and remove unused variables.
Unused variables will be indicated with a prefix of an underscore.
This will help with pylint tests to ignore them and general housekeeping.

commit_message:
Fix instance cross AZ check when attaching volumes

For CONF.cinder_cross_az_attach=False, we currently only check the desired AZ
during scheduling but don't actually check the final AZ of the node.

When attaching volumes to running instances we need to check the actual
AZ on the instance and not the desired AZ at boot time. The desired AZ
attribute is optional at boot and may not be set or the desired AZ
could be different from the final AZ.
When we are booting with a volume however we don't know the final AZ so we
check on the desired AZ.

Closes-Bug: #1255347
Change-Id: Ied912c171100a450754d315027bf5c407ac067bb
(cherry picked from commit 18a1486293b15c5713ac1352b9b9b30fdf2b7413)

commit_message:
Make backtick detection more reliable

Change the regular expression to not match ` in a line which is a
comment. Removes a large number of false positives when people
are in the habit of using RST in their comments.

Change-Id: I562d4ce80021470c839e784e233535fecf2a0c77

commit_message:
Fix check_fixed_network_cidr for nova network

* Replace 'nova network-list' with 'nova net-list'
  in check_fixed_network_cidr function;
* Add network checks to Jenkins 'bvt_2' and 'smoke' tests
  ('TestHaVLAN' and 'deploy_simple_cinder')
* Fix default local patches to local repositories in settings.py

Change-Id: I859e308e3d1b4ff360b5e730275b21868e775d9f
Closes-Bug: #1381586

commit_message:
Improves the query_to_kwargs method

Currently, the timestamp in query fields is not unified.
start_timestamp/end_timestamp and start/end shouldn't be supported in some
APIs, this patch improves the query_to_kwargs method to forbid these in
query fields.

Change-Id: I37c7fb4bfa26b22e6591140f974c85b23b77b060
Partial-Bug: #1291171

subject: Improves the query_to_kwargs method

commit_message:
Improves the query_to_kwargs method

Currently, the timestamp in query fields is not unified.
start_timestamp/end_timestamp and start/end shouldn't be supported in some
APIs, this patch improves the query_to_kwargs method to forbid these in
query field.
This patch transform timestamp db function's params base the commit #92066

Change-Id: Id5f7a7d80ea089bd93caad20e7879e2c2c34bda4
Closes-bug: #1295104

commit_message:
Update glance.openstack.common 

1. Sync openstack.common modules up to latest version
from oslo-inc. The follow modules got updated: 
 * fileutils
 * install_venv_common
 * lockutils
 * log
 * processutils

2. Add _i18n module as the dependency for new code.

3. Remove openstack.common.test module.
Glance and dependencies now use oslotest instead.

4. Remote unused openstack.common.excutils module.
Glance now use the module from oslo.utils instead.

5. Add missing modules back to openstack-common.conf.
Below ones are still using currently. But they will
be removed when the latest policy module get synced.
 * jsonutils
 * strutils

Change-Id: Ibbc2cda81a4e3c13643fe5c5bf6471c3f544add7
Signed-off-by: Zhi Yan Liu <zhiyanl@cn.ibm.com>

commit_message:
Hoist duplicated AlarmService initialization to super

api_client and _load_evaluators was duplicated across each service,
presumably needlessly*.

Discovered via pylint complaining about use of unitialize api_client
member.

* If there is a specific need for it to be otherwise that needs to
be made more clear.

Change-Id: I118edce87abd0e26ee0e963f44535b355a3752d0

Hi John,
I think this is neat idea and could be a useful feature.  The only problem is the spec doesn't include any details or even a hint of how you'd implement this.

So... How would this be implemented?  How would you configure and set it up? How would you issue a call for this from the API?

Most of all... what flushes the data from fast-cache to the Cinder Volume?

I don't think this "relieves pressure from the backend storage server" at all, but it does offer a nice performance gain if you can work through all the details.   Caching like this isn't trivial IMHO so I'd love to see some detail in the spec and maybe even some POC.'}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2014-10-16 04:21:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Agree with John Griffith that this is a nice idea but need more details.

It looks like you submitted the spec directly to the cinder repository.  Spec should be submitted to cinder-specs repository: https://github.com/openstack/cinder-specs. 
It should be added to specs/kilo folder.'}, {'account_id': 13437, 'date': '2014-10-16 08:35:23.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

wrong commit'}]

Setting up repo for master Juno Branch

* Update metadata version
* Removing Strainer file
* Adding Gemfile.lock to .gitignore
* Updating Gems
  * chef (11.12.0)
  * chefspec (4.0.0)
  * rspec (3.0.0)

commit_message:
Reduce extraneous test output

The tests generate a large amount of extraneous logging output.
This due to the manage utility, when tested via test_manage,
setting up logging in it's own way. Monkey patching the log.setup
call to a no-op during tests prevents this.

Also fixed an incorrect usage of assert which was causing a
warning to be generated.

Change-Id: I6b8724142c0812d84e697e280acc0264620f6a2b

commit_message:
Fix ttl and grace story for claims updates

Claim's updates are currently extending the life of a claim by extending
its `ttl` without taking into account the claim's grace. In addition to
this, the `ttl`'s default value is 60 for claim's renewal instead of
being the value of the configured default ttl.

This patch allows users to specify a `grace` when renewing a claim. If
`grace` is not present, it'll use the configured default value for it.

The change doesn't break backwards compatibility as in v1_0 a ttl *is*
required for claims renewal.

Closes-bug: #1356184
Change-Id: I9cce93c65f6d14ed8fabbbbcb9bf7ddc3bc11af2

commit_message:
Fix an encoding exception when creating a public_url

When using urlparse.quote, the string needs to be utf8 encoded,
or an exception is thrown.

Change-Id: I1e3d4abc136fbbbd03a54789f3df0855ceea98e1
Closes-Bug: 1346386
Co-Authored-By: Cédric Soulas <cedric.soulas@cloudwatt.com>

[{'created': '2014-07-02 13:53:11.000000000', 'message': 'Add svc-map to cinder-api

This patch integrates svc-map into the cinder-api element
by adding a svc-map json file and using the os-svc-enable
script in the parent review.  This code follows the same
conventions as the pkg-map patch[1] that landed recently.

The svc-map json file provides a means to map service names
inside the element itself instead of using map-services in
the respective os element in diskimage-builder.  The svc-map
file in the cinder-api element uses the service names from
the redhat and suse families as the default name and maps
to the different name used in the debian family.

The modification to 73-cinder-api uses the new syntax to
call os-svc-enable passing it the service key name and the
element to map for.

[1] Ic0a061995e2ae708c95a535cba6237bff58f7d93

Change-Id: Ib3bc5c47de1b8bb6006530d56e9d47c3763af7b5

commit_message:
Add svc-map to cinder-api

This patch integrates svc-map into the cinder-api element
by adding a svc-map yaml file and updating os-svc-* calls
to use the -a option so svc-map is called instead of
map-services.  Please see the svc-map integration commit[1]
for more information on implementation details as needed.

[1] I382631746e458f2f8603a7dcf5221a21f4b53255

Change-Id: Ib3bc5c47de1b8bb6006530d56e9d47c3763af7b5

Thanks for this, most of it is exactly what I'd expect.

I have just one question about sending repeated backup.create.start notifications. Do you have any examples from other projects where progress notification is handled in this way? I've had a quick look through nova, but I didn't see any.

Do you think this is the 'correct' way to do this, are there alternatives, like sending a 'create.progress' notification?"}, {'account_id': 2243, 'date': '2014-07-08 04:06:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-2

Waiting for response to Ollie's questions... I'll gladly remove my -2 but it seems this is the only way to get attention :)"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-08 04:06:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: -Verified

Starting check jobs.
http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-08 04:06:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

Build succeeded.

- noop http://logs.openstack.org/47/104747/4/check/noop/bcd2539 : SUCCESS'}, {'account_id': 2861, 'date': '2014-07-08 07:07:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Thank you, Oliver. To be honest, I did not see the progres notification in other projects either. I suggest the process of backing up to swift can be divided into three steps: prepare back, create data and update metadata. I suggest eah of them has a separate event notification. Please refer to the new spec i have just submitted.

To report the progress of creating data, I suggest to use createdata.progress as the event suffix.'}, {'account_id': 2861, 'date': '2014-07-08 07:08:14.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-08 07:08:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Starting check jobs.
http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-08 07:08:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

Build succeeded.

- noop http://logs.openstack.org/47/104747/5/check/noop/d8ab64d : SUCCESS'}, {'account_id': 4355, 'date': '2014-07-08 07:42:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

I don't think notifications should be driver-dependent.  If I switch from Swift to Ceph tomorrow, I'd expect to see the same notifications in Ceilometer."}, {'account_id': 1773, 'date': '2014-07-08 16:38:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Given that the most important application of the ceilometer is for billing, I also think that most people's needs would be met by the create.start/end and delete.start/end notifications. 

It *might* be useful to allow drivers to give periodic progress notifications, but the prepare data and update metadata notifications don't seem useful to me. 

For example it might be useful sometime to update the swift driver to update the metadata periodically while the backup is being created, so that a backup that was interrupted could be continued. The notifications could make that more difficult if people were depending on it."}, {'account_id': 2861, 'date': '2014-07-10 01:59:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

In three of the backup service types, swift is the only one, which is able to send the notification in the progress of sending data, because the the data is split into chunks/swift objects and we send them one by one in a while loop. For TSM and ceph, we cannot break the progress when sending the data to the backup service.

Since we can't make the progress notification general for all the backup services, shall I remove it from the spec? Or is there any other suggestion?"}, {'account_id': 1773, 'date': '2014-07-10 08:04:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

The bp could say something like 'Drivers may send a create.progress notifications periodically. If a drivers does send periodic notifications the period should be configurable.'"}, {'account_id': 2861, 'date': '2014-07-11 08:39:33.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-11 08:39:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-11 08:39:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified+1

commit_message:
Propose: Add the notification support to the backup service

The volume backup service needs to send the notifications to ceilometer
to report the usage stats for the volume backup during backup create,
delete and restore. In addition, progress notification support will be
added for some backup drivers, which can send periodic notifications
to Ceilometer.

Related to blueprint backup-notification

Change-Id: Ic55403ba83f8ec6b6c7a6a77135d4687c71659bb

commit_message:
Schema enhancement to support MultiSegment Network

Currently, there is nothing in the schema that ensures segments
for a network are returned in the same order they were specified
when the network was created, or even in a deterministic order.
Closes-Bug: #1224978

Change-Id: I9e0bdb2cd98b1a25377703356345bd89c7189dc6

commit_message:
Alarms listing based on "timestamp"

Currently, Alarms are listed based on "Alarm_id". This fix will order it according to the "Timestamp"

Change-Id: I81e6b671f3eed53a6261d50286f586390510b2ab
Fixes bug #1287119

Get Alarms ordered by name

Alarms are ordered at storage level.
Existing test (test_alarm_history_with_on_behalf_of_filter)
has also been changed as alarms are ordered by name now.

Change-Id: I3fa11c8859266a99343abe4a266ffb675e6beb5a

I'm seeing a weird side effect after applying this patch. When I go to the 'Launch Instance' dialog and select 'Boot from image (creates a new volume)', the 'Device size' field gets populated with the string "admin". Is anyone else seeing this?'}, {'account_id': 8674, 'date': '2014-02-17 11:10:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

Hi Ana,

I just noticed this, and after a lot of search (I dumped the html to a file before sending it to the browser) I discovered that it's the browser who prefills the form (the username is not in the html and not set by JS either).

Now I wonder why the browser does this mistake.
It's not "admin" prefilled by the browser, but the username you logged in with.

Looks like the browser mistakes it with a login form...

I wonder if the following patch would not solve it?:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/68381/
Since it prefills the volume size.'}, {'account_id': 9317, 'date': '2014-02-17 12:00:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

I just tested the two patches together. https://review.openstack.org/#/c/68381/ does prefill the device size, but only after the image has been selected. So the problem with the username being populated into the device size field remains.'}, {'account_id': 8674, 'date': '2014-02-17 12:11:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

I tried changing the CharField to IntegerField, it doesn't help (Is there a reason why it's a Charfield even though it has to be an Integer?)
I'm investigating why the browser prefeills this field."}, {'account_id': 8674, 'date': '2014-02-17 12:59:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

Hi Ana,

Even weirder: The "Acces & Security" tab also prefills the "Admin Pass" field with the user's login password (If you allowed your browser to remember the password).

The hard part is that there's nothing to see in the code, it's the browser which adds the login and password by prefilling the form. If you override the render method to dump the html in a file, those fields are totally empty.

Even when inspecting the form ("Firebug" or FireFox's integrated inspector), the fields are shown as empty...

I didn't see this in my first tests, however, I rebased since when I added the unitests. So something might have changed in the form making the browser prefill fields it shouldn't by mistaking them with the login form fields. This is weird because the field's IDs are well specific to the instance form.'}, {'account_id': 8674, 'date': '2014-02-17 13:57:21.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-02-17 13:57:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

commit_message:
Hiding device name field when unhandled

When OPENSTACK_HYPERVISOR_FEATURES['can_set_mount_point'] is set to false
we hide the device_name field in the launch_instance form

Change-Id: Id5eacbfc7fb230320e0d0bc8bcc839e285844f86
Closes-Bug: 1273298

commit_message:
Handle Forbidden error from network_api.show_port in os-interface:show

We can get a 403 back from the neutronv2 API when calling
network_api.show_port so handle that in the compute API extension.

This also updates the v3 API code to match the v2 API code to put the
original error message for the 404 into the HTTPNotFound error.

Closes-Bug: #1378389

Change-Id: I7afc832f26481dc44f1c500b6121e2060f36c63a

commit_message:
Port os-networks-associate plugin to v2.1(v3) infrastructure

Ports os-networks-associate extension and adapts it to the
v2.1/v3 API framework. API behaviour is identical.

- unittest code modified to share testing with both v2/v2.1
- Adds expected error decorators for API methods

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: I6ccf9613abf999784c548fb058522ac60db7f052

commit_message:
Port os-tenant-networks plugin to v2.1(v3) infrastructure

Ports os-tenant-networks extension and adapts it to the v2.1/v3 API
framework. API behaviour is identical.

- unittest code modified to share testing with both v2/v2.1
- Adds expected error decorators for API methods

Partially implements blueprint v2-on-v3-api

Change-Id: I340c9b1312a3477c63d28f19df9611c95e67cde6

commit_message:
Fix possible race condition for accept transfer

Accept transfer API workflow is currently like this:

  call volume_api.accept_transfer()
    |
    --- RPC cast to volume manager
          |
          --- volume manager calls volume driver accept_transfer()

  update volume's DB record

Given the non-blocking nature of RPC cast, what happens in volume
manager and volume driver can happen in parallel with the DB update.
If volume driver relies on original DB record to do things, then
DB record shouldn't be updated until volume driver finishes its job.

So this patch change volume RPC API accept_transfer() from cast
to call to make sure the workflow is in serialized manner.  Also
elevated the context when volume manager tries to update the DB
record when driver has done accept_transfer().

Closes-bug: #1357432

Conflicts:
    cinder/volume/rpcapi.py

Change-Id: Ieae52e167aa02967338e0be5d78d570d682faa7a
(cherry picked from commit 7e95b05b937e632ae8aee82cfa8f6f31835e6316)

commit_message:
Optimize get_instance_nw_info and remove ipam

The get network info was making 4 * num_networks + 1 rpc and db
queries. The network info is recalculated quite often, so we use
the new joins to turn this into a single query. In the process we
remove nova_ipam_lib which was initially created as part of a very
old neutron proxy and only added an unnecessary layer of abstraction.

Change-Id: I34ca575fb33b43ab8780357990b73df837da71c2
Closes-Bug: #1365606

commit_message:
Try to stop test_cage from failing as much

This patch adds a rety decorator around the assert in hope to allow more time
for the message to be recieved which has an undeterministic arrival time. This
code should probably be refactored in the future to remove testing something
undeterministic like this.

Change-Id: I207adc52c97f6bd909475925f2e75748198a5a82
closes-bug: #1379927

commit_message:
Remove sslutils from openstack.common

This module has been imported but is not used. Let's remove it.

Change-Id: I0cafdb7ddc00ce58b0724cee293f5dad6f4a1817

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-11 12:22:02.000000000', 'message': "Fix KeyError exceptions in dhcp_rpc when port_update happens

For the action 'create_port', DhcpRpcCallback._port_action()
function is called with the 'port' dictionary as
port = {'port': {'network_id': 'foo_net_id', ...}

For the action 'update_port', _port_action() function
is called with the 'port' dictionary as
port = {'id': foo_id, 'port': {'port': 'network_id': foo_net_id ...}}

This function is not taking this into account when
accessing 'network_id' and 'fixed_ips' and hence there is
KeyError if some exception occures for 'update_port' action.

This patch fixes this issue.

Change-Id: I70b92fa20b421b05ca2053a9a57f62db726f7625
Closes-bug: #1378508
"}, {'created': '2014-10-12 20:17:35.000000000', 'message': "Fix KeyError in dhcp_rpc when plugin.port_update raise exception

KeyError exception is seen because of following reasons

* DhcpRpcCallback._port_action() is called by two functions
   -  DhcpRpcCallback.create_dchp_port()
   -  DhcpRpcCallback.update_dhcp_port()

* When create_dhcp_port() function calls _port_action(), the
  function argument 'port' will have the body as
  {'port': {'network_id': foo_network_id, 'fixed_ips': [..] ...}

* When update_dhcp_port() function calls _port_action(), the
  function argument 'port' will have the body as
  {'id': port_id, 'port': {{'port': {'network_id': foo_network_id,
			            'fixed_ips': [..] ...}}

* If an exception occurs when _port_action() calls plugin.create_port(),
  network id is accessed as
  net_id = port['port']['network_id']

* If an exception occurs when _port_action() calls plugin.update_port(),
  network id is accessed as
  net_id = port['port']['network_id']
  which is causing the KeyError. network_id should have been accessed as
  net_id = port['port']['port']['network_id']

This patch fixes the issue by making the _port_action() take the
same port body. update_dhcp_port() insteading of passing the port_id
and port information in a single argument, it now sends the port_id
as a separate argument and passes port information AS IS.

Change-Id: I70b92fa20b421b05ca2053a9a57f62db726f7625
Closes-bug: #1378508

commit_message:
Fix KeyError in dhcp_rpc when plugin.port_update raise exception

KeyError exception is seen because of following reasons

* DhcpRpcCallback._port_action() is called by two functions
   -  DhcpRpcCallback.create_dchp_port()
   -  DhcpRpcCallback.update_dhcp_port()

* When create_dhcp_port() function calls _port_action(), the
  function argument 'port' will have the body as
  {'port': {'network_id': foo_network_id, 'fixed_ips': [..] ...}

* When update_dhcp_port() function calls _port_action(), the
  function argument 'port' will have the body as
  {'id': port_id, 'port': {{'port': {'network_id': foo_network_id,
			            'fixed_ips': [..] ...}}

* If an exception occurs when _port_action() calls plugin.create_port(),
  network id is accessed as
  net_id = port['port']['network_id']

* If an exception occurs when _port_action() calls plugin.update_port(),
  network id is accessed as
  net_id = port['port']['network_id']
  which is causing the KeyError. network_id should have been accessed as
  net_id = port['port']['port']['network_id']

This patch fixes the issue by making the _port_action() take the
same port body. update_dhcp_port() insteading of passing the port_id
and port information in a single argument, it now adds port_id
in the port body itself.

- https://review.openstack.org/#/c/122880

The DBDuplicateError will be handled by the patch 
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/126793/

commit_message:
Call DVR VMARP notify outside of transaction

The dvr vmarp table update notification was being called inside
of the delete_port transaction in ML2, which can cause a yield
and lead to the glorious mysql/eventlet deadlock.

This patch moves it outside the transaction and adjusts it to
use an existing port dictionary rather than re-looking it up since
the port is now gone from the DB by the time it is called.

Closes-Bug: #1377241
Change-Id: I0b4dac61e49b2a926353f8478e421cd1a70be038

commit_message:
Use EUI64 for IPv6 SLAAC when subnet is specified

This commit uses EUI64 for SLAAC and stateless IPv6 address
when subnet id in fixed_ip is specified.

After this patch, all the ports created on a subnet which has
ipv6_address_mod=slaac or ipv6_address_mod=dhcpv6-stateless
will use EUI64 as the address.
This patch also checks if fixed IP address is specified
for a IPv6 subnet with address mode slaac or dhcpv6-stateless
during creating or updating a port. If yes, raise InvalidInput
error to stop the port creation or update.

Remove unit test test_generated_duplicate_ip_ipv6 because
fixed_ip should not be specified for a slaac subnet.

Change-Id: Ie481cfb2f4313baf44bf1a838ebda374a5c74c6a
Closes-Bug: 1330826

commit_message:
remove E251 exemption from pep8 check

This change removes the exemption for E251 by addressing unexpected spaces
around keyword/parameter equals

Change-Id: Iff17477e37bef2a97fc58a538d08bcfc35c67751
Partial-Bug: 1329017

commit_message:
Remove an argument that is never used

This code was creating a dict with a gw_exists key.  I was curious to
know who was interested in receiving this information down the line.
However, no one is ever interested in that key.  It took me some time
to follow this through wondering what was going on and found only dead
ends.

Change-Id: I755d9628ab750b950b33f5dcf32ccf2a9b00800e

commit_message:
Catch exceptions in router rescheduler

Catch and log exceptions in router rescheduling loop
rather than just dying which would stop all future
router rescheduling attempts.

This prevents transient DB connectivity issues from
permanently breaking the rescheduler until the process
restarts.

Closes-Bug: #1375597
Change-Id: I2ab37847074fa6bbdd2b13fd03b8742996dcfc78

[{'created': '2014-09-04 11:59:01.000000000', 'message': "Don't define virsh secret if already defined

We test to see if the ceph secret already has been defined before
installing the secret again.

This is mainly done to keep our Foreman runs clean, as it reports
on hosts that have had changes applied. Without the 'unless' clause
any node that has the nova compute class installed will report as
having changes applied.

Change-Id: I05e83f07570d4a0e67a700bd9d9030eef1c261c3
(cherry picked from commit 69b7a3c36645630aa668fe60639417fcbc24ce32)
"}]
commit_message:
Don't define virsh secret if already defined

We test to see if the ceph secret already has been defined before
installing the secret again.

This is mainly done to keep our Foreman runs clean, as it reports
on hosts that have had changes applied. Without the 'unless' clause
any node that has the nova compute class installed will report as
having changes applied.

Change-Id: I05e83f07570d4a0e67a700bd9d9030eef1c261c3
(cherry picked from commit 69b7a3c36645630aa668fe60639417fcbc24ce32)

commit_message:
Hyper-V: add support for attaching volumes via SMB

Currently, the Hyper-V driver only allows attaching volumes via iSCSI.
The purpose of this blueprint is adding support for attaching volumes
hosted on a SMB share.

bp hyper-v-smbfs-volume-support

commit_message:
Add lock status into output of instance detail view

Currently we only support locking/unlocking an instance but we are not able
to query whether the instance is locked or not.
This proposal is to add the lock status to the detailed view of an instance.

blue print link:
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/nova/+spec/get-lock-status-of-instance

Change-Id: I5d6e42849a61e68fbbe05c92752fa6584505d5bf

commit_message:
Makes kombu_ssl_* parameters optional when rabbit_use_ssl => true

The kombu_ssl_* parameters should not be required when rabbit_use_ssl => true
Rather, rabbit_use_ssl must be set to true if the kombu_ssl_* parameters are
used.

Change-Id: Ia3d71eaccdfb736068478b935e5be46719eb49db
Closes-Bug: 1356083
(cherry picked from commit 141e65a7ddc07b682fc730bab98bffbd7d49f53f)

commit_message:
Join enabled_ssl_apis array

Adds a stdlib join() to the enabled_ssl_apis so we can specify more than one.

Closes bug: #1360978

Change-Id: Ifd290fea802fc926a9e34076393c2c55c3cd9cf5

[{'created': '2014-02-13 21:59:45.000000000', 'message': "Restrict the length of user name input

There is an allowed maximum length for user name field, but in current
code, it doesn't check or restrict that from UI side, i.e. user will be
able to type in more than what is allowed. After form submission, it
will fail but there is no clear message telling user what caused
failure.

After adding the code to restrict the max length of the user name field,
user will not be able to input more than what is allowed, thus this
error will be prevented from UI.

Change-Id: Id41e44d3ed648826210069cacc8369ed59c75669
Closes-Bug: #1279579
"}]
commit_message:
Restrict the length of user name input

There is an allowed maximum length for user name field, but in current
code, it doesn't check or restrict that from UI side, i.e. user will be
able to type in more than what is allowed. After form submission, it
will fail but there is no clear message telling user what caused
failure.

After adding the code to restrict the max length of the user name field,
user will not be able to input more than what is allowed, thus this
error will be prevented from UI.

Change-Id: Id41e44d3ed648826210069cacc8369ed59c75669
Closes-Bug: #1279579

commit_message:
Makes kombu_ssl_* parameters optional when rabbit_use_ssl => true

The kombu_ssl_* parameters should not be required when rabbit_use_ssl => true
Rather, rabbit_use_ssl must be set to true if the kombu_ssl_* parameters are
used.

Change-Id: If9cceb4f4090c8b39079aa1aae2f53640c9ac0ff
Closes-Bug: 1356083
(cherry picked from commit a4a20a9012114ee21ad175422d3a9d5f0ab41120)

commit_message:
Makes ca_file parameter optional when use_ssl => true

The ca_file parameter should not be required when use_ssl => true.  Rather,
use_ssl must be true when ca_file is specified.

Change-Id: Ifb4b5acccdce0be63e763b4d837eb452827cd6d4
Closes-Bug: 1356089
(cherry picked from commit 70ef4af1e7c5b42a4ebabdbd6d2f69623c8861f5)

commit_message:
Add extended logging options.

There is a range of extended logging options in Openstack services that use
openstack.common.logger (Ceilometer, Cinder, Heat, Keystone, Nova). Adding
ceilometer::logging to support them.

No blueprint/spec, as discussed in the IRC meeting on 08-11-2014.

Change-Id: I910e2f9e4f3ad1991d58ba6df16adfbc85e20131
(cherry picked from commit 078deea6169bb148e3d31743c2060a19f20e0fcc)

commit_message:
Add extended logging options.

There is a range of extended logging options in Openstack services that use
openstack.common.logger (Ceilometer, Cinder, Heat, Keystone, Nova). Adding
heat::logging to support them. This change is identical to
<https://review.openstack.org/#/c/113560/> but it applies to puppet-heat
instead of puppet-ceilometer.

No blueprint/spec, as discussed in the IRC meeting on 08-11-2014.

Change-Id: Ia120b799d676e516d8e593088f93d44891c20cbd
(cherry picked from commit 2492ef5fb35258251b41fc692ff7e2b8043e9c0f)

commit_message:
Add extended logging options.

There is a range of extended logging options in Openstack services that use
openstack.common.logger (Ceilometer, Cinder, Heat, Keystone, Nova). Adding
keystone::logging to support them. This change is identical to
<https://review.openstack.org/#/c/113560/> but it applies to puppet-keystone
instead of puppet-ceilometer.

No blueprint/spec, as discussed in the IRC meeting on 08-11-2014.

Change-Id: I88fcf025b9467090d21d1a10a5af9b270f8ef11e
(cherry picked from commit f277297080251ec2fe789363c3c5dd0877c9435d)

[{'created': '2014-10-14 13:41:24.000000000', 'message': 'Set volume_driver for iscsi backend explicitly

Setting the volume_driver option explicitly even for iscsi backend is
desirable, because if the user would switch from e.g. an nfs backend
to iscsi, the volume_driver config option would not be changed during
the Puppet run and still point to the nfs driver.

Defaults to LVMISCSIDriver, can be overriden to LVMISERDriver.

Change-Id: I860508ff92fce4add21c50e684e1717fc4f16622
(cherry picked from commit 0f67be560c7b95d80555fd4fd4cd794274bf7d8a)
'}]
commit_message:
Set volume_driver for iscsi backend explicitly

Setting the volume_driver option explicitly even for iscsi backend is
desirable, because if the user would switch from e.g. an nfs backend
to iscsi, the volume_driver config option would not be changed during
the Puppet run and still point to the nfs driver.

Defaults to LVMISCSIDriver, can be overriden to LVMISERDriver.

Change-Id: I860508ff92fce4add21c50e684e1717fc4f16622
(cherry picked from commit 0f67be560c7b95d80555fd4fd4cd794274bf7d8a)

_formset_table_row.html missing i18n tag.

commit_message:
Adds support for Glance Tasks calls

Add tasks operations on client side to support task create,
list all and show.

DocImpact
Implement blueprint async-glance-workers

Change-Id: Ib4b8e347a8a47817e3b427c8ba024e8c32f65155

commit_message:
Explicit complaint about old OpenSSL when testing

Running the tests with an old version of OpenSSL
results in many tests breaking without any hints
of the real cause. This handles that explictly,
stopping execution whenever the version is older
than 1.0 and exiting with an informative message.

Co-Authored-By: Rodrigo Duarte Sousa <rodrigods@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>
Closes-Bug: 1225084

Change-Id: I55e151d3fb4ddbe5ee4bf64bfdc597b4da73f6bb

commit_message:
Update python-ldap version used for testing

We are currently pinned to an old version of python-ldap for our
test requirements.  Version 2.4 of python-ldap has been out for
over 3 years now, and most platforms are shipping it.  We should be
testing against it instead of using an old version.

Change-Id: If33cb1207dc9c463c8602999f31948ca65199089

commit_message:
Add ability to extract a list of versions

Add ability to extract a list of know versions from the service
catalog.  Currently at least, the service catalog contains versions.
The get_versions method returns either a list of versions or an
[] empty list if the service catalog doesn't contain a detectable
version.  If the service catalog does not contain a service, None
is returned.

Change-Id: I207553ca4bdd0083aff1802182039dde6ab72148

The assertValidEntity method in test_v3 is used for validating
whether the entity returned by api has correct keys. This method
allows user to specific which key fields to check - but if no
specification is given then it will check for 'name', 'description'
and 'enabled'. Currently, all the keystone resources are validated
by this method. But, actually the keystone resources do not have
some of the same attributes at all. So, I think the keys to check by
default would be an empty list.

commit_message:
remove default check keys in assertValidEntity

The assertValidEntity method in test_v3 is used for validating
whether the entity returned by api has correct keys. This method
allows user to specific which key fields to check - but if no
specification is given then it will check for 'name', 'description'
and 'enabled'. Currently, all the keystone resources are validated
by this method. But, actually the keystone resources do not have
some of the same attributes at all. So, I think the keys to check by
default would be an empty list.

Change-Id: Ic039c379e8686fb7385e162798c5a15ad2f2e789
Closes-Bug: #1350593

commit_message:
Make the the assertValid<Entity> calls internal.

There are many assertValid<Entity> calls in test_v3.py. Now, they
are expected to only do special checks. So, we should make them
internal.

Change-Id: I721fb53922ac6174cf691d6a89160ecb568c08c9

commit_message:
Replace httpretty with requests-mock

We've had some issue in the past with httpretty breaking compatability
between releases and being a problem to package upstream. requests-mock
is on stackforge and can be tailored to our needs.

Due to issues with py34 and httpretty, this is the preferred fix to
allow middleware to test against py34 (instead of waiting for a fix to
httpretty).

Change-Id: I9fa0f12c732eb187fcb5b0926593cb3624ddc51a

commit_message:
Actually test interactive password prompt

* keystoneclient/tests/v2_0/test_shell.py
(ShellTests.test_user_create_password_prompt): Remove the password
from the calling environment and fake out the check for an
interactive terminal session so that the code which implements
password prompting will actually be exercised.

Change-Id: I46f45553995316c7d006a83897413d57e127e48c

commit_message:
NetApp fix eseries concurrent vol map failure

This fixes the issue while mapping volume to host
when the requests are very close in time proximity.
The map operation has been synchronized.

Change-Id: I2e120d84d3b96faa4ab8d4324e70a089bcddeaa5
Closes-bug: #1312685
(cherry picked from commit 209c09a76f5e90aaa2899804686e6a513703d887)

[{'created': '2014-10-14 04:50:35.000000000', 'message': 'Add flake8 2.2.4

Flake8 2.2.4 Fix bugs triggered by turning multiprocessing on by default.

The move to flake8 2.2.4 is done in two steps since our
global-requirements system does not allow non-overlapping changes.

Change-Id: Ifb1c91ccfac7dd71ef0641f3a8660b4e492ecfa4
'}]
commit_message:
Add flake8 2.2.4

Flake8 2.2.4 Fix bugs triggered by turning multiprocessing on by default.

The move to flake8 2.2.4 is done in two steps since our
global-requirements system does not allow non-overlapping changes.

Change-Id: Ifb1c91ccfac7dd71ef0641f3a8660b4e492ecfa4

subject: Run router dashboard unit tests by default
messages:
[{'account_id': 6620, 'date': '2014-10-09 16:02:19.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 6620, 'date': '2014-10-09 16:12:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

This bug was created to fix the non-running of certain dashboard unit tests relating to networks and instances with the use of 'profiles'. Those tests were never running by default and was finally fixed in Juno-2. 
The problem persists in stable/icehouse also and it is better to get that resolved.

Additionally - bug 1260435 highlights the fact that the update profiles in the router dashboard is broken. This bug was fixed in Juno but needs to be backported to stable/icehouse. In order for that to be backported without issue, this UT fix needs to be backported as well, if possible.

commit_message:
Run router dashboard unit tests by default

Currently the "router" dashboard does not have its unit tests
run by default. This was beacuse the dashboard needed to be
turned on for these tests to be run and turning on this dashboard
was not mandatory.

However, now that the dashboards are pluggable, turning on the
router dashboard tests, and more specifically the Cisco N1K profile
tests is doable and necessary. This fix aims to remove the checks
put in place to run the tests only when the dashboard is available
and instead now run all the tests mandatorily

This fix was merged in J-2. Backporting to stable/icehouse
so that the 'router' dashboard and tests using profile
are run in Icehouse as well.
-----

cherry picked from commit 2f2312dfcccda1b421a80f27e6759d67f4df6ba1

Conflicts:

	openstack_dashboard/dashboards/project/instances/tests.py

    def test_launch_instance_post_with_profile(self):
        self.test_launch_instance_post(test_with_profile=True)

Note - Fixed 2 string messages in create_instance.py so as to
not affect translation and retain previous messages.
Additionally, fixed minor pep8 errors in instances/test.py
and networks/tests.py

Closes-bug: #1229819
Change-Id: I3c77a71db08ac611e5bdf9274af5a558bfda3327

commit_message:
Add missing newline to stderr output when argument value is wrong

For example when having an argument with possible choices and the used
choice is not available the stderr output is like the following example.

argument --formatting: Invalid String(choices=['check', 'fix']) value: fixaberendt@zitrone

To have the shell prompt at the next line it necessary to at '\n' at the
end of the stderr output.

Change-Id: I99152e69bb090ea5d7102cc85d60498c3c6213eb

commit_message:
Allow user to select different visibilities

A service may have one default visibility, but the user should
be allowed to override that.  For example listing tenants is
an administrative function by default, but is also available
over the public interface.  This will work:

    python examples/list.py openstack/identity/v2/tenant.py --os-api-visibility public

Change-Id: I4e40e55f9f7c369a9c3e900712a89fdbc743ffcb

commit_message:
Add user preference and example CLI to build it

Add a user preference class to collect user service preferences.

Sorry for all the test changes.  I wanted to make the v2 and v3
tests have the same service catalog in a different format so that
the normalize catalog would be the same for both.

Closes-Bug: #1353030

commit_message:
Fix E127 errors in remaining openstack_dashboard/

E127 continuation line over-indented for visual indent

Also fixes E127 introduces by other reviews
after other E127 fixes were merged.

Closes-Bug: #1375931
Change-Id: I0a09f1c2f74c707fc8a347f0ea5975bf2679976e

commit_message:
Improve list groups roles performance

Uses GET v3/role_assignments?scope.project.id=<project_id>
to fetch groups roles in a given project, instead of doing
an individual call for every known group.

Closes-Bug: 1369137
Change-Id: Ie64dfddc0d8cbb4f22f3ee3b19c248ca6973e96c

commit_message:
WIP Implement stateless floating ip forwarding

In the current implementation, conntrack is wasted on floating ips.
There is not reason for it except that we don't have a way to
implement it without touching conntrack.  If we could implement
floating ips in a stateless way that didn't touch conntrack then this
could be both a performance improvement and a security improvement.

Change-Id: I1866d71a2ae7c394dc33eca6e235853f54a3b51e
Related-Bug: #1334926

commit_message:
Configures haproxy to serve novnc_proxy

This patch configures haproxy to serve novnc_proxy which currently
listens on 0.0.0.0. So before this patch goes in novnc needs to be
listening on local-ipv4 like the rest of the services. The following
patch does that in image-elements.

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/125326/

Change-Id: I0c6a3d6a8fd10da71abbf568633b28bdb5e56aa2

commit_message:
Make haproxy timeout configurable

We are hitting haproxy server timeouts sometimes so making
these values configurable so that we can tune them via heat.

Change-Id: I83d219e076229fe58eec13ad99432c4770accc8d

commit_message:
Add Nova Admin access to neutron.conf

Add Nova admin access information to Neutron to allow it to do
vif callbacks.

messages:

- gate-openstack-manuals-tox-checklang http://logs.openstack.org/94/127494/1/check/gate-openstack-manuals-tox-checklang/af78017 : SUCCESS in 11m 03s (non-voting)'}, {'account_id': 9515, 'date': '2014-10-10 14:32:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

RHEL/CentOS/Fedora still need this step.'}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2014-10-10 14:34:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Have they not changed to UUID by default? When running keystone-manage pki_setup there is a not that PKI should not be used in production environments. I think if Fedora, .. are still using PKI we should add a note how to change the token backend to the project default.'}, {'account_id': 9515, 'date': '2014-10-10 15:15:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I'm not sure what you mean. From what I can tell, Ubuntu/SUSE run some SSL commands during the installation. RHEL/CentOS/Fedora run them using this step."}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2014-10-10 15:18:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Yes. But those steps are only necessary when using PKI as token backend. This changed in Juno. The default token backend is now UUID.'}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2014-10-10 15:19:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Default token provider. Not token backend, sorry. More details at https://blueprints.launchpad.net/keystone/+spec/uuid-as-default-token-provider .'}, {'account_id': 9515, 'date': '2014-10-13 16:50:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Workflow-1

Needs further testing on RHEL/CentOS/Fedora.'}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2014-10-14 09:21:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Matt, what to test there? I will ask on the RDO mailing list if the default will change to UUID with Juno.'}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2014-10-14 09:23:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Dropped a mail at rdo-list@redhat.com.'}, {'account_id': 1955, 'date': '2014-10-14 22:23:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

openstack-keystone RPM does not modify upstream default
i.e. [token] provider is not set in http://pkgs.fedoraproject.org/cgit/openstack-keystone.git/tree/keystone-dist.conf

puppet-keystone modules was setting this to pki earlier but that was changed to match Juno:
https://github.com/stackforge/puppet-keystone/commit/611d9649f21c304af3c34475b42e3b04822c8639
This is included in the latest RDO Juno build openstack-puppet-modules-2014.2.1-0.4

I also double-checked that packstack is not setting token_provider parameter.

So all good for RDO Juno!'}, {'account_id': 9515, 'date': '2014-10-14 22:34:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 -Workflow

Thanks for investigating.'}, {'account_id': 9098, 'date': '2014-10-14 22:37:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

We still need to perform the PKI certificate setup, even if UUID tokens are being used.  The reason is that the token revocation list is signed regardless of the token format.  If the keys/cert are not created, then an attempt to fetch the revocation list will result in signing errors due to an underlying ENOENT.  There are some more details related to this here:

  https://bugs.launchpad.net/puppet-keystone/+bug/1373064
  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/123547/'}, {'account_id': 9515, 'date': '2014-10-14 23:05:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

The Ubuntu keystone server package continues to automatically generate certificates during the post-installation process... perhaps for this reason.'}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2014-10-15 12:31:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Ok. I think then we have to only remove the following sentence:

By default, the Identity service uses public key infrastructure (PKI).'}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2014-10-15 12:34:32.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 9515, 'date': '2014-10-15 12:41:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2

I think this works.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-15 12:46:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

commit_message:
Fix instructions for installing ceilometer controller on SUSE based distributions

Because MongoDB is not available in Cloud:OpenStack:Juno it is necessary
to add an additional repository first.

Also the systemctl commands for openSUSE are missing at the moment.

Change-Id: Ibfdb933da0adc6921c1235f9c577bdfef57ff81e

Revert "Migrate mysql backend to use openstacklib::db::mysql"

mysql backend using openstacklib::db::mysql is not supported by the old
 version of puppetlabs/mysql used in fuel

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-10 13:13:18.000000000', 'message': "Fix ttl and grace story for claims updates

Claim's updates are currently extending the life of a claim by extending
its `ttl` without taking into account the claim's grace. In addition to
this, the `ttl`'s default value is 60 for claim's renewal instead of
being the value of the configured default ttl.

This patch allows users to specify a `grace` when renewing a claim. If
`grace` is not present, it'll use the configured default value for it.

The change doesn't break backwards compatibility as in v1_0 a ttl *is*
required for claims renewal.

Closes-bug: #1356184
Change-Id: I9cce93c65f6d14ed8fabbbbcb9bf7ddc3bc11af2
"}, {'created': '2014-10-10 15:06:46.000000000', 'message': "Fix ttl and grace story for claims updates

Claim's updates are currently extending the life of a claim by extending
its `ttl` without taking into account the claim's grace. In addition to

commit_message:
Fix ttl and grace story for claims updates

Claim's updates are currently extending the life of a claim by extending
its `ttl` without taking into account the claim's grace. In addition to
this, the `ttl`'s default value is 60 for claim's renewal instead of
being the value of the configured default ttl.

This patch allows users to specify a `grace` when renewing a claim. If
`grace` is not present, it'll use the configured default value for it.

The change doesn't break backwards compatibility as in v1_0 a ttl *is*
required for claims renewal.

Closes-bug: #1356184
Change-Id: I9cce93c65f6d14ed8fabbbbcb9bf7ddc3bc11af2

[{'created': '2014-10-14 22:14:27.000000000', 'message': 'Revert "Allow multi-line config items in meta-section of local.conf"

This reverts commit 6ff21acf4c4d4ef08bbef419ba582cade4da8da7.

This commit has broken config options with colons in them.
The following is a sample configuration that no longer works:

[[post-config|/etc/neutron/plugins/ml2/ml2_conf.ini]]
[restproxy]
server_ssl=False
servers=10.211.1.9:80
server_ssl=False

With the above config and the code present that this reverts,
the 'servers' option will come out blank.

Change-Id: I328852d2d941605051a1bf5eaf0f7674191f8c48
'}]
commit_message:
Revert "Allow multi-line config items in meta-section of local.conf"

This reverts commit 6ff21acf4c4d4ef08bbef419ba582cade4da8da7.

This commit has broken config options with colons in them.
The following is a sample configuration that no longer works:

[[post-config|/etc/neutron/plugins/ml2/ml2_conf.ini]]
[restproxy]
server_ssl=False
servers=10.211.1.9:80
server_ssl=False

With the above config and the code present that this reverts,
the 'servers' option will come out blank.

Change-Id: I328852d2d941605051a1bf5eaf0f7674191f8c48

commit_message:
Add support for cciss p seperator in ceph-osd fact

the facter code was subsituting the ! in the cciss device, but had forgotten
 about the p seperator between the device and partation number.

the patch adds the p seperator if the ! is matched in the gsub to the remaining
 locations that would need the p seperator to properly refrence devices.

Change-Id: I5054cde345495b62fa66f3ae3876fc6eb098cc5c
Closes-bug: 1381218

commit_message:
Remove Puppet unit tests for version 2.7

Puppet 2.7 is no longer supported, and the major distros
are now up to 3.x.  So it makes sense to remove testing
against this version in the gate.

However, there are comments here that Puppet 2.7 support
was planned to continue until spring 2015.  So I will leave
it up to the group on whether or not we are close enough
to that threshold to remove it.

Change-Id: I3791328d743f2424d84aad1d206a7317ba5a84e3

commit_message:
Increase CEPH_LOOPBACK_DISK_SIZE for ceph

check-tempest-dsvm-full-ceph is failing due to space
contraints in the Ceph store.  Increase the size of this
store to alleviate this problem.

Change-Id: I753cee181b7a4e4de36840407f9cfbaafc4802a6

[{'created': '2014-10-15 16:23:02.000000000', 'message': 'Handle poorly formed individual sensor readings

ipmitool returns a series of multiple readings per run. Some of
these readings may be of a form that parser code cannot handle. The
desired behavior in this case is for the single reading to be
dropped and for parsing to continue. This change ensures that
behavior by continuing through the loop instead of allowing
exceptions to cause the loop to exit.

Tests have been added which verify the correct behavior.

Note that though there was an opportunity to log each skipped
reading this would lead to a very large number of log messages as

Closes-Bug: #1381600
'}]
commit_message:
Handle poorly formed individual sensor readings

ipmitool returns a series of multiple readings per run. Some of
these readings may be of a form that parser code cannot handle. The
desired behavior in this case is for the single reading to be
dropped and for parsing to continue. This change ensures that
behavior by continuing through the loop instead of allowing
exceptions to cause the loop to exit.

Tests have been added which verify the correct behavior.

Note that though there was an opportunity to log each skipped
reading this would lead to a very large number of log messages as
many or even most samples from ipmitool are not parsed.

Change-Id: I6a3193d5a6e12c69ca5c548e5fb58d8bc9646348
Closes-Bug: #1381600

commit_message:
Default to the "scale" deployment mode

Defaulting to "poc" means that we by default use a mode with less features,
which means people wonder where that feature has gone.

Change-Id: I6a29c8dfcc5d176c3ccbd4ff0945e3b9568fb0d1

commit_message:
Start the testenv client in a new process group

If the command being run by the testenv client hits the timeout, we kill
the entire process group of the testenv client. This will include
the bash process being run by zuul and may cause zuul to rerun the job.
Starting the testenv-client in a new process group should leave
toci_gate_test.sh process alone.

Change-Id: If908485ca25458e5272505fd52ece1d21bedecda

commit_message:
Add support for cciss p seperator in ceph-osd fact

the facter code was subsituting the ! in the cciss device, but had forgotten
 about the p seperator between the device and partation number.

the patch adds the p seperator if the ! is matched in the gsub to the remaining
 locations that would need the p seperator to properly refrence devices.

Change-Id: I5054cde345495b62fa66f3ae3876fc6eb098cc5c
Closes-bug: 1381218

commit_message:
Break out port binding logic from ML2 plugin

This is done by introducing the concept of a
BindingManager. Some of the rationale below:

DVR extensions and (possibly) extensions for
hierarchical-port-binding have (will) unveil(ed) the
close coupling between some of the logic around port
binding management.

This is an initial step towards breaking this
coupling, making the binding logic separate and
extensible. Next step will target ways to address
a more general data model that will be able to target
the usual case, as well as both distributed and
multi-level bindings.

Supports-blueprint: ml2-hierarchical-port-binding
Supports-blueprint: neutron-ovs-dvr

Change-Id: I6cec1a69556c2965e346026d6bf1c0128e92cdc9

commit_message:
Set tempest storage protocol for Ceph job

Without this, jobs fail due to tempest using an iSCSI protocol
spec when trying to create a volume.

Change-Id: Ibbf41f443fe8465d89dcc4fc7369887cd7926a40

commit_message:
Force heartbeat immediately after async command completes

This change passes the agent object into extensions, such that
they may call agent methods as needed. It also causes async
commands to force a heartbeat immediately after completing the
command. This allows Ironic to get a heartbeat and continue
work as quickly as possible, while also allowing deployers to
configure Ironic (agent) to heartbeat less often.

Change-Id: Ib3c3a43dfd0ed4ed51b7d52ac099f01181ca822f

commit_message:
Add the PXE VendorPassthru interface to PXEDracDriver

Without the PXE VendorPassthru interface to expose the "pass_deploy_info"
method in the vendor_passthru endpoint of the API the DRAC it can't
continue the deployment after the ramdisk is booted.

Closes-Bug: #1379705
Change-Id: I21042cbb95a486742abfcb430471d01cd73b3a4a
(cherry picked from commit 78ec7d5336eb65ff845da7ea9f93d34b402f5a0f)

[{'created': '2014-10-15 09:31:04.000000000', 'message': 'Fix unit test failure due to tests sharing mocks

A recent refactor made test_get_port_vnic_info 2 and 3 share code
in a private method _test_get_port_vnic_info(). A mock on this method
is shared between the tests and can cause the following failure:

AssertionError: Expected to be called once. Called 2 times.

This is changed so that the two test methods create separate mocks and
pass to the shared method.

Change-Id: I3902b7b7cf4b4b3fdc2885bf2611a712d008c617
Closes-Bug: #1381414
'}]
commit_message:
Fix unit test failure due to tests sharing mocks

A recent refactor made test_get_port_vnic_info 2 and 3 share code
in a private method _test_get_port_vnic_info(). A mock on this method
is shared between the tests and can cause the following failure:

AssertionError: Expected to be called once. Called 2 times.

This is changed so that the two test methods create separate mocks and
pass to the shared method.

Can this be configurable? I don't think we want to be computing this md5 on the proxy. And if thats true then do we have to use the multipart MIME stuff at all? The problem that this solves is not really worth the overhead that this patch involves."}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2014-10-06 18:02:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Yeah, I know it's not really worth it here. The thing is we've got a bunch of stuff coming up that'll need this sort of functionality. I thought about just building this on the EC branch, but not everyone looks at that, and I didn't want a "surprise! MIME!" moment when EC got closer to merging.

Basically, for EC, the proxy has to compute the etag. An object server can't do it because it only gets this EC-archive thingy, and that has different bytes in it; the only thing that actually sees the object, as passed from the client, is the proxy server.

Then there's this crypto thing that popped up recently; if we do end up doing something cryptographimacal, it'll be in the same boat. The proxy will be the only one with the plaintext object's bytes, so it'll have to be the one computing and checking the etag.

I completely agree with you that this particular use case isn't really worth all the complexity, though. I just wanted to make sure that folks weren't suddenly surprised by a bunch of MIME, and I also didn't want to introduce some bunch of weird protocol baloney that was never actually used.'}, {'account_id': 7479, 'date': '2014-10-13 18:23:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1

(1 comment)

So I've still got a lot more tinkering to do with this to understand everything but so far it makes sense (mostly)...."}, {'account_id': 7479, 'date': '2014-10-13 18:25:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

dfg: how would you feel if the etag computation were configurable but the general MIME support was not?  There are other ways to do what we need for EC but this seemed like a logical/generic way to go'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2014-10-13 18:34:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 995, 'date': '2014-10-15 15:42:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Paul, that would be fine to just make the md5 configurable. The main thing is i don't want all the extra overhead that would cause."}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2014-10-15 17:27:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

If it's the MD5 and not the MIME that's objectionable, then we'll go ahead and merge just the MIME onto feature/ec. It's all proposed and everything.

If you're using EC, then your proxies will end up MD5-ing objects since they're the only things with a complete view, but replicated objects won't get hashed until the object servers."}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2014-10-15 17:27:38.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

MIME stuff is going onto feature/ec, the rest isn't important"}]

[{'created': '2014-09-29 21:53:56.000000000', 'message': "Make proxy compute object etag if not sent by client

Currently, if a client makes a PUT request and does not send the Etag
header, each object server computes the Etag individually. If there is
data corruption between the proxy and an object server, Swift can end
up with two good copies and one corrupt copy of the object, but both
having the same timestamp. Neither replication nor auditing cleans
this up.

This commit makes the proxy compute the md5 of the object and send it
in a footer *after* the object has been sent to the backends. This is
all in the same request, not two separate ones. The object server
checks it and rejects the PUT if the proxy-sent etag doesn't match the
computed one, just like with the client-supplied etag.

The proxy only does this if the client didn't send an etag. If the
client did send one, everything continues working like it does today.

Bonus fix: make the proxy send etags (in the headers, not a footer)
for object COPY requests, not including SLO and DLO.

The wire format is a multipart MIME document. For sanity during a
rolling upgrade, the multipart MIME document is only sent to the
object server if it indicates, via 100 Continue header, that it knows
how to consume it.

Example 1 (new proxy, new obj server):

   proxy: PUT /p/a/c/o
          X-Backend-Obj-Metadata-Footer: yes

     obj: 100 Continue
        X-Obj-Metadata-Footer: yes

   proxy: --MIMEmimeMIMEmime...

Example2: (new proxy, old obj server)

   proxy: PUT /p/a/c/o
          X-Backend-Obj-Metadata-Footer: yes

     obj: 100 Continue

   proxy: <obj body>

This is also beneficial for EC work, as it provides a general
mechanism for sending header values *after* the request body. EC will
need this to store the object's original Etag if the client doesn't
send it since the object servers won't be able to compute it.

Change-Id: I347d98f8a732da510d6ab17b95130a5b6f0a8d76

commit_message:
Make proxy compute object etag if not sent by client

Currently, if a client makes a PUT request and does not send the Etag
header, each object server computes the Etag individually. If there is
data corruption between the proxy and an object server, Swift can end
up with two good copies and one corrupt copy of the object, but both
having the same timestamp. Neither replication nor auditing cleans
this up.

This commit makes the proxy compute the md5 of the object and send it
in a footer *after* the object has been sent to the backends. This is
all in the same request, not two separate ones. The object server
checks it and rejects the PUT if the proxy-sent etag doesn't match the
computed one, just like with the client-supplied etag.

The proxy only does this if the client didn't send an etag. If the
client did send one, everything continues working like it does today.

Bonus fix: make the proxy send etags (in the headers, not a footer)
for object COPY requests, not including SLO and DLO.

The wire format is a multipart MIME document. For sanity during a
rolling upgrade, the multipart MIME document is only sent to the
object server if it indicates, via 100 Continue header, that it knows
how to consume it.

Example 1 (new proxy, new obj server):

   proxy: PUT /p/a/c/o
          X-Backend-Obj-Metadata-Footer: yes

     obj: 100 Continue
        X-Obj-Metadata-Footer: yes

   proxy: --MIMEmimeMIMEmime...

Example2: (new proxy, old obj server)

   proxy: PUT /p/a/c/o
          X-Backend-Obj-Metadata-Footer: yes

     obj: 100 Continue

   proxy: <obj body>

This is also beneficial for EC work, as it provides a general
mechanism for sending header values *after* the request body. EC will
need this to store the object's original Etag if the client doesn't
send it since the object servers won't be able to compute it.

[{'created': '2014-07-28 06:50:54.000000000', 'message': "Pass errors from detach methods back to api proc

The initial implementation of the detach_interface method was built as
cast invocations.  The respective attach method was built as a call
invocation.  What this led to was, if the user attempted to attach an
incorrect port, that error would be passed back up to the API
properly.

However, if the user attempted to detach an invalid interface, the
response from the API would be an HTTP 202 (because the cast assumes
success).  The root error may be logged in the respective nova compute
log, but it did not make its way back up to the user.

This change updates the decorators to the manager methods to update
the instance's fault when the attach or detach encounters an issue.

Change-Id: I111b1c8a492f12587f86ab83825060029605390d
Closes-Bug: #1339098
"}]
commit_message:
Pass errors from detach methods back to api proc

The initial implementation of the detach_interface method was built as
cast invocations.  The respective attach method was built as a call
invocation.  What this led to was, if the user attempted to attach an
incorrect port, that error would be passed back up to the API
properly.

However, if the user attempted to detach an invalid interface, the
response from the API would be an HTTP 202 (because the cast assumes
success).  The root error may be logged in the respective nova compute
log, but it did not make its way back up to the user.

This change updates the decorators to the manager methods to update
the instance's fault when the attach or detach encounters an issue.

Change-Id: I111b1c8a492f12587f86ab83825060029605390d
Closes-Bug: #1339098

commit_message:
Make user creation optional when creating service.

In some cases it is useful to be able to just configure
the service in Keystone and not the service user. This
is the case when e.g. a read only LDAP backend is used.
Added parameters configure_user and configure_user_role
(default to true).

Change-Id: If3d53c2c9070691b4731142f512b1f4bb754be00
Closes-Bug: 1360232

commit_message:
Ensure groups leaving returns are gotten

Since the leave_group logic may be async we want to make
sure we at least try to get() the results of the leave calls
made, instead of dropping them on the floor (which is bad).

Change-Id: Ie86fae14170fe4ce0db6ccbf6eb999d998ff10fc

[{'created': '2014-10-13 17:21:34.000000000', 'message': "Make rest_client.wait_for_resource_deletion timeout error more specific

Currently the timeout error message just says 'Failed to delete resource
within the required time' and includes the test class/test case, but
when we're seeing all volume-related tests racing with a delete hang, we
can't fingerprint an elastic-recheck query on the various test
class/test case names, and there aren't errors in the cinder logs.

The best thing we have to fingerprint is the timeout message, but we
need it to be more specific to the type of resource rather than any
resource type that might have timed out during a delete operation.

This is similar to the is_resource_deleted method in the various rest
clients in that the concrete implementations on the base class return
their specific type so we can use that in the timeout message.

Closes-Bug: #1380712

Change-Id: I36b49c59daa95219c4377d1e207ea4a0c8cf8782

commit_message:
Make rest_client.wait_for_resource_deletion timeout error more specific

Currently the timeout error message just says 'Failed to delete resource
within the required time' and includes the test class/test case, but
when we're seeing all volume-related tests racing with a delete hang, we
can't fingerprint an elastic-recheck query on the various test
class/test case names, and there aren't errors in the cinder logs.

The best thing we have to fingerprint is the timeout message, but we
need it to be more specific to the type of resource rather than any
resource type that might have timed out during a delete operation.

This is similar to the is_resource_deleted method in the various rest
clients in that the concrete implementations of the base class return
their specific type so we can use that in the timeout message.

Closes-Bug: #1380712

Change-Id: I36b49c59daa95219c4377d1e207ea4a0c8cf8782

commit_message:
B64-decode Shelved keys

It seems shelve stores its objects as base64-encoded strings.
This change decodes those strings so we can evaluate the hashes
properly.

Change-Id: I118411875fb929f1cd5379cb303a1253e863f281

commit_message:
Clarify deprecation comment to be accurate

The planned change in functionality was delayed until Juno,
the original comment was written in IceHouse. There needs to be
a period of two cycles for deprecation.

N.B: No functional change in this patch, just change of comment.

Change-Id: I3f452fbda59358fe85c1d7060a4abebd2f7c311a

Don't use a specific arg list for stress in tox.ini

Callers should be able to specify the arguments.

[{'created': '2014-10-14 17:12:02.000000000', 'message': "Avoid clobbering existing class definition

Using the same variable name for a new class implies that an
existing class is being modified whereas what's happening is that a
subclass is being created of an existing class and having a
different value for an attribute. Such an implication is confusing
for maintainability.

Change-Id: If784949e8b5706e881bc702ff0b30848bca17d5c
"}]
commit_message:
Avoid clobbering existing class definition

Using the same variable name for a new class implies that an
existing class is being modified whereas what's happening is that a
subclass is being created of an existing class and having a
different value for an attribute. Such an implication is confusing
for maintainability.

Change-Id: If784949e8b5706e881bc702ff0b30848bca17d5c

commit_message:
Clean up tox.ini and make tempest and unit test distinct

This commit creates a separate base env for tempest tests and
tempest's unit tests. However, to keep the same interface the tempest
env is setup by overloading the testenv using substitution from a
common base section.

As part of this internal reorganization in the tox.ini several other
things are cleaned up or removed. Usless or duplicate job definitions
are removed. The unit tests are switched to pretty_tox. Previously
they were run without any output which made it difficult to figure out
exactly what was running. Additionally, this removes the unnecessary
regex filter on the unit test job. The unit tests use a different
discovery path so there is no need to also filter it on the same path
this will allow the use of more specific regexes with tox to filter
tests.

Change-Id: I996d81dec2739bbe907f5fe87a335994c01697b3

commit_message:
Easier to read console output

The console output was hard to read because it was displayed on one
line as a string as part of a tuple. Split them up so it's readable.

Change-Id: Ieb59909802a587027c4691924e70923c61476591

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-13 07:23:13.000000000', 'message': "Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910
"}]
commit_message:
Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910

commit_message:
Added link to resource

To complete the configuration for firewall to allow VNC, a VIB is
required. The doc did not show how to obtain the VIB. Added a note
with a link to the git repo containing the package.

Change-Id: Ibd744023764c1b9b89d38bd632fb5d63df9058e9
Closes-Bug: #1295199

commit_message:
Remove docutils pin

This was added to work around bug 1091333.  A new sphinx has been
released and so this is no longer necessary.

Also update sphinx requirements from global requirements.

Change-Id: I9107884d964757a9154bdd1feb4ea6df4e9df43e

commit_message:
Ensure $TMPDIR exists

There are some situations (use of libpam-tmpdir) where the $TMPDIR is
defined but the dir path is not existing. Check for it and create
where necessary.

Change-Id: I4db808cc1c5b5f2b205c07601ffef31b6b6fc389
Closes-Bug: #1330290

Closes-Bug: #1381266
Related-Bug: #1376680

'}]
commit_message:
Increase tolerance of install DHCP

For Ubuntu, added the following kernel options:
netcfg/link_detection_timeout=20
netcfg/dhcptimeout=120
For CentOS:
dhcptimeout=120

Closes-Bug: #1381266
Related-Bug: #1376680
Related-Bug: #1379917
blueprint 100-nodes-support

Change-Id: I3e5f687590a145ba174d19d392bdbb73d4d9a11e

commit_message:
Move to final release of CentOS7 images

This is the final released image; it is the same one deployed in many
cloud provers such as HP and AWS.  It is also safe from all known
vulnerabilities up to its release

[{'created': '2014-08-18 17:49:06.000000000', 'message': "Make sure volumes are well detected during block migration

Currently, _assert_dest_node_has_enough_disk() calls
self.get_instance_disk_info(instance['name']), which means that
get_instance_disk_info() has a block_device_info parameter equal to None, and
_get_instance_disk_info() as well. In the end, block_device_info_get_mapping()
returns an empty list, and the 'volume_devices' variable is an empty set.
Ultimately, this prevents volume devices from being properly detected in
_get_instance_disk_info(), and Nova tries to migrate them as well, even though
they should not be migrated.

Fix this issue by passing 'block_device_info' to
check_can_live_migrate_source() and have it propagated all the way to
_get_instance_disk_info().

commit_message:
libvirt: Make sure volumes are well detected during block migration

Current implementation of live migration in libvirt incorrectly includes
block devices on shared storage (e.g., NFS) when computing destination
storage requirements. Since these volumes are already on shared storage
they do not need to be migrated. As a result, migration fails if the
amount of free space on the shared drive is less than the size of the
volume to be migrated. The problem is addressed by adding a
block_device_info parameter to check_can_live_migrate_source() to allow
volumes to be filtered correctly when computing migration space
requirements.

This only fixes the issue on libvirt: it is unclear whether other
implementations suffer from the same issue.

Thanks to Florent Flament for spotting and fixing an issue while trying out
this patch.

Co-Authored-By: Florent Flament <florent.flament@cloudwatt.com>
Change-Id: Iac7d2cd2a70800fd89864463ca45c030c47411b0
Closes-Bug: #1356552

commit_message:
Increase tolerance of install DHCP

For Ubuntu, added the following kernel options:
netcfg/link_detection_timeout=20
netcfg/dhcptimeout=120
For CentOS:
dhcptimeout=120

Closes-Bug: #1381266
Related-Bug: #1376680
Related-Bug: #1379917
blueprint 100-nodes-support

Change-Id: I3e5f687590a145ba174d19d392bdbb73d4d9a11e

commit_message:
Increases the number of processes in CentOS 6.X 

Increases the number of processes per user in /etc/security/limits.d/90-nproc.conf
for CentOS 6.X due to bug https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=919793

Change-Id: I76f258f33325f80fe06167dec08d81dabd292163
Closes-Bug: 1376564

Correct int datatypes during zone import

During a zone import, many integer fields are being incorrectly
cast to strings before being passed to central.

Change-Id: Icba1053012b449fb2ba507c3b6080298ccf98e01
