commit_message:
Using Neutron names in Sahara

Sahara Cluster benchmarks and Cluster context now works with
Neutron network name.

A resource type added to handle name to id conversion.

Some minor improvements are also done to test and context classes.

Change-Id: I8e567747c28630bc7c1efeb834947bf778c03e49

commit_message:
Track the attempted method when raising UnsupportedVersion

This helps in circumstances where the only stacktrace visible
is on the target side (e.g. due to cast or fanout operations)
and without the method information is difficult to root cause
what is going on.

Change-Id: I070ecda4d56186fcda8e8bfc49bf723928998393
Closes-bug: #1340277

commit_message:
Remove unused modules copied from oslo-incubator

No longer needed since we moved to oslo.utils and
oslo.serialization and updated to latest oslo-incubator.
As part of the cleanup removed the hack for gettextutils
since the oslo-incubator code no longer uses it

Change-Id: Ib020cd4c3464f1c994a6d77f4b894f41b99e6d02

From #openstack-neutron on freenode:

dims: pete5, reading through, if we go down the _authenticate_with_neutronclient route, we will need consensus from neutron devs, also if we want to get rid of neutron_auth_strategy (to switch just to keystone). can you please ping them to give us guidance? personally i am ok either way and the approach of looking at expires is very promising. Only issue would be if someone is using a nclientv20.Client with a token that eventually expires which was one of the first problems that led us to where we are now

[1:14pm] pete5: dims: the neutronclient approach does take expiration into account. it's just a hack because getting at the token expiration information requires looking at its internal keystone token data structures. Perhaps when neutronclient adds support for more auth strategies, it can also add a proper interface for retrieving the token expiration."}, {'account_id': 7500, 'date': '2013-12-05 18:19:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

While working on this review that touches all of the clients that nova talks to (cinder/glance/neutron):

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/84522/

We're trying to generalize things.

All of these client connections take a token, but it seems we are putting a lot of time and energy into making the neutronclient connection as solid as possible, maybe because that's the one that's used the most or the hardest?

Anyway, wondering if we should step back and think about actually doing something across all of these clients for handling tokens - basically taking the caching and sharing concepts here and also making them available with the cinder/glance client modules in nova.

Any thoughts on that?"}, {'account_id': 8802, 'date': '2014-05-01 14:42:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

I like the idea of generalization and will be happy to join the effort.

However, don't you think we need to solve the problem first and then optimize?

commit_message:
share neutron admin auth tokens

Admin tokens in nova.network.neutronv2 were being created once per
"thread" (i.e., green thread) and shared. For example, during instance
creation, a single token was created then reused 6 times.  However,
this scheme was far from optimal. Given that tokens, by default, have
a shelf life of 24H, a single token can be shared by _all_ admin
nova.network.neutronv2 calls in a 24-hour period.

DocImpact
Signed-Off-By: Peter Feiner <peter@gridcentric.ca>
Closes-Bug: 1255594

Change-Id: I5c743aa86030e4ab000dcdefb6a7183305512303

Agree with boden - better to convert in one place than multiple places. Would the _untranslate_volume_summary_view() in nova/volume/cinder.api be a better place to handle this?'}, {'account_id': 9555, 'date': '2014-09-26 09:41:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Ed, the short answer is no. This gets confusing because we're looking at 2 separate sets of metadata here:

* Volume summary info
This is the volume's own metadata. Cinder serializes this correctly and Nova receives it with the correct type. _untranslate_volume_summary_view() is simply shuffling this about, but it's already correctly typed.

* Image metadata, stored by cinder
This is the glance metadata which is stored as key/value pairs by cinder, and returned along with the volume metadata by cinder. This is the metadata Nova wants when booting from a volume. It *also* contains a size, but because cinder stored it all as a blob it has lost its type information. Therefore *this* size is a string.

However, given that size, specifically, is no longer a property of the original image, we should probably take it from the volume. I'll probably update this patch."}, {'account_id': 9555, 'date': '2014-09-26 11:17:54.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-26 13:29:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

commit_message:
Fix image metadata returned for volumes

When creating a volume from a glance image, cinder stores the original
image metadata in volume_glance_metadata. This is a key/value store,
and all the values are strings.

When Nova boots an instance from a volume, it passes the image
metadata returned by cinder, which is all strings. If a driver
expects these values to be ints, as they are when booting from an
image, it will get a type error.

This change also pulls size from the volume directly rather than
taking the value from the stored image metadata. This is because the
volume will have been created in 1Gb increments, and is unlikely to be
the same size as the original image. It may also have been
subsequently extended.

Change-Id: I7928f6be1ca99f1502941b9df2b443f2ca63a37b
Closes-Bug: #1367540

commit_message:
VMware: get_all_cluster_refs_by_name default to {}

Currently get_all_cluster_refs_by_name returns None when no cluster
is found.
driver.py is using the keys() method without checking whether the
object returned is None. This can potentially end up throwing an
AttributeError.

This patch fixes the issue by returning an empty dictionary when no
cluster is found.

Change-Id: I3293c916d79aaa4de8913e8ab9c609c9c0bb023e
Closes-Bug: #1372672

commit_message:
add tool for finding users of deleted modules

This script scans the config files for projects to find anything trying
to use a module that has been removed from the incubator.

Change-Id: Icb168ca64785f24909b47bce8faf3324d2ba94ab

[{'created': '2014-10-15 09:00:38.000000000', 'message': "Change ThreadGroupManager.remove_event() to be compatible with greenthread callback

remove_event() in 'ThreadGroupManager' class was declared as,
    def remove_event(self, gt, stack_id, event)

while it is called in _resolve_links() of greenthread
    f, ca, ckw = exit_funcs.popleft()
    f(self, *ca, **ckw)

They are incompatible.

Change-Id: I72c0e1207fc6e84b3441f18ed89e7788ad1f3746
Closes-Bug: 1381381
"}]
commit_message:
Change ThreadGroupManager.remove_event() to be compatible with greenthread callback

remove_event() in 'ThreadGroupManager' class was declared as,
    def remove_event(self, gt, stack_id, event)

while it is called in _resolve_links() of greenthread
    f, ca, ckw = exit_funcs.popleft()
    f(self, *ca, **ckw)

They are incompatible.

Change-Id: I72c0e1207fc6e84b3441f18ed89e7788ad1f3746
Closes-Bug: 1381381

commit_message:
Refresh nova-network after nova_config

Nova-network was being started too soon and
did not have necessary configuration,
leading to instances without network access.

Change-Id: Icdbc40fa28bb30fe9490740cc044440e2778c63e
Closes-Bug: #1380672

Tasklib implementation in python

Medium between configuration providers and fuel orchestration
solution.

check README.md and functional tests for better understanding
how it works

HOW TO RUN:

taskcmd -c tasklib/tests/functional/conf.yaml run puppet/sleep

taskcmd -c tasklib/tests/functional/conf.yaml run exec/fail

taskcmd -c tasklib/tests/functional/conf.yaml daemon exec/long
taskcmd -c tasklib/tests/functional/conf.yaml status exec/long

Related to blueprint granular-deployment-based-on-tasks

Change-Id: Ifed1a9b90042bbbc93215a30dfb34e29dbe8fba2

Nailgun/Fuel-agent integration

This change adds provision method radio bottom on
cluster settings tab. It also adds image info into
release fixtures.

commit_message:
Map host puppet manifests if testmode is enabled

Connects /etc/puppet to containers for testmode
option. It makes deployment with custom puppet
manifests for testing easier.

Depends: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/110982/

Change-Id: If6f0c3a1ae37033a5ea6345e61ba79472a7e03f0
Implements: blueprint fuel-master-ci-tests

commit_message:
Removed sleep in execute util in fuel-agent

Sometimes when parted performs some action
it fails to re-read updated partition table
on a disk. It occurs mostly when you run parted
command several times without delay. We had
sleep(1) in execute utility as a fast workaround.

Looks like the issue can be addressed with just
additional call or partprobe right after failed
parted command. This patch impelemnts this
assumption.

But it is still not a real fix, it is again just
a workaround. Real fix is to launch parted one time
for every disk passing to it a whole table
(all partition at once). We are going to implement
this as soon as possible, right after addressing
most prioritized issues.

Change-Id: I539800271260c3d3f1b3560f8111ba8b6cacc9c4
Implements: blueprint image-based-provisioning

[{'created': '2014-09-21 18:29:31.000000000', 'message': "rsyslogd config templates: remove invalid comments

rsyslogd version 7.x (which is shipped with Ubuntu 14.04) does not support
comments inside multi-line statements:

if ($programname == 'foo') \
 # some comment here
then -/var/log/foo.log

rsyslogd treats such a comment as a fatal error and refuses to start.
Remove those broken comments to avoid the error.

Change-Id: I7f5efc9ec5096777b58f7ec6576947d1d36d8ecd
"}]
commit_message:
rsyslogd config templates: remove invalid comments

rsyslogd version 7.x (which is shipped with Ubuntu 14.04) does not support
comments inside multi-line statements:

if ($programname == 'foo') \
 # some comment here
then -/var/log/foo.log

rsyslogd treats such a comment as a fatal error and refuses to start.
Remove those broken comments to avoid the error.

Change-Id: I7f5efc9ec5096777b58f7ec6576947d1d36d8ecd

commit_message:
Increase verbosity of Firewall check results

Create dump of iptables rules before running check
and increase verbosity of log message if test fails.
Also do not remove temporary check file, just rename it.

Change-Id: I55fa25e7ef0d2a42899b98600297741ad53d931c
Closes-bug: #1378745
(cherry picked from commit 82e1c6e502f5094bf1ff91dc8f5dd4e7c5aab094)

commit_message:
Fix LVM iSCSI driver tgtadm CHAP authentication

Currently CHAP Authentication in LVM iSCSI driver with tgtadm does not work.
This is because the tgtadm helper creates the target configuration file
with an 'IncomingUser' entry, which is ignored by tgtd.
This patch fixes it to 'incominguser'.

Change-Id: I14871985a2a916834122f849238f05b75726bc1a
Closes-Bug: #1329214
(cherry picked from commit e3563891545c801726d227f752cf99488ed5c7dd)

commit_message:
image-create with non-optional argument

Additional non-optional argument name add to
v1 and v2 shell. nargs causes that is optional,
because of fail check tests. This proposal fix
causes later need changes in devstack, but invoke
will be consistency with other glance method:
glance image-update and glance image-delete.

Closes-Bug: 1134463
Change-Id: I7a7b64f281fdc406b817ca1f2690ab8bf7f6630f

commit_message:
Add additional checks for patching tests

Added:
- check if os services restarted
- check dep versions on slaves
- temporary disable tests for rollback

Change-Id: Ic91b76857cce16220a41f58829fbc9764c92de43
Related-bug: #1356873

Fixed region duplication

Keysone resource expects name of the OpenStack service
but $region/$service is provided

commit_message:
Download image API to bypass vCenter

This patch introduces a new API to download images. This new API
provides a new signature which gives the ability to bypass vCenter
when downloading images.

Change-Id: Id3cf3f03e1d0622a99573bd090b8ea6b397765e0

commit_message:
Fix duplicate ref of volume_types_client in vol tests

tempest/api/volume/base.py admin base tests class has duplicate
reference for 'volume_types_client'. Tests use mix of both.

This patch fix this duplicate reference and modify tests accordingly

Closes-Bug: #1379106

Change-Id: I016d364ad792c97d1dce12ee7da225ebe0a690f6

commit_message:
glance image-create with required image name argument

Decorate method do_image_create in v1/shell and v2/shell
with 'name' parameter as not optional. In v2/shell 'name'
pop from 'fields', which is needs to invoke gc.images.create
properly. Two tests case change for this, because there is
need to pass the image name as first param.

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: 1134463
Change-Id: I9f3d163b6af9c572f7e31e830266be5c4fd73dac

I commented the code to indicate that the variable does not have to be set in the configuration file -- the scripts will work without it. But I did put it there to document that the option exists.

I like flexible code and I don't mind adding new options that allow users to change some aspects of the program behavior, but I'd rather avoid configuration files filled with mandatory options that most people never use. Therefore, sane defaults should exist outside of the user's configuration file.

So yes, it is intentional, but I have no problem changing it. Do you think it would be better to uncomment the line?"}, {'account_id': 11889, 'date': '2014-10-14 21:38:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I think it could be a bit confusing. Could you please put in the comment line above that you can use this to override the default value of 8000 MB?

Maybe just something like:

commit_message:
labs: add BASE_DISK_SIZE configuration option

A new configuration option, BASE_DISK_SIZE, allows users to change the
size of the disk available to the node VMs.

Because the disks grow dynamically, the cost of larger disks is limited
in practice to additional time spent in zero_empty.sh.

Change-Id: I47a72a08cfa51ba6c04306b64e04c4c2600975dd

commit_message:
Avoid shutting off a paused VM instance

Currently, "Shut Off Instance" option is enabled even on a paused VM instance
which results in an error that says "Error: Unable to shut off instance".
With this commit, we are removing the option to shut off a paused VM instance.

Change-Id: I95da413a398632d9300333a4dbaf028b7c6a6f68
Closes-Bug: #1372620

commit_message:
Change saml2.ADFSUnscopedToken method signature.

In saml.ADFSUnscopedToken __init__ signature should first list options
from the parent class (identity_provider, identity_provider_url,
username, password), and only later plugin-specific arguments. That's
why ADFS specific ``service_provider_endpoint`` should be moved after
``password``. This change will also be useful in Saml2Wrapper
(https://review.openstack.org/#/c/106751/).

Change-Id: Ibeae836e6328a58a1bcf8b792c6be0e8d6ac41a7

commit_message:
Prevent clicking on buttons and links until DOM is loaded

Do so in order to prevent non-ajax request for buttons/links
which are supposed to initiate only ajax requests leading
to modal form appearance.

Change-Id: Ibfa1d7e25e4f8a74f3062ad8162c7a089dd7dd87
Closes-Bug: #1328540

commit_message:
Set force_snat_range to ANY network

Due to change 59ac254bf15bb059cca12a82c9d819c371ea5c6f
Nova-network checks whether network has external gateway
and does (which it has by default) and does not create SNAT
rules for the instances if list of force snat ranges is empty
now.

This change sets force_snat_range to ANY network and thus
new code adds corresponding rules.

Change-Id: I8d22a2564dfcd8e81543d7a25089a0e7af3ca2b3
Closes-bug: #1381164

commit_message:
unlock VLAN Manager radiobutton from Network tabs

Now nova-network works properly in VLAN Manager mode. But element on UI
for setting this mode currently locked. It will be unlocked by this patch.

Change-Id: I75c11686f1bc3c8f2f9cf0442348b079b5d3f4a1

commit_message:
restart_required cfg-param is bool and not string

There was a break to the previous version of the configuration
paramenters API when the configurations parameters were moved to
the database. The actual type of the restart_required parameter
should be a JSON boolean value, and not a string to be compatible
with the previous configuration parameters API.

Change-Id: If45944e25a55813ddf8f80010811da04d667ca19
Closes-Bug: #1379665

commit_message:
Fixes KeyError in floating ip unit test

Patch 118478 introduced security group create buttons respecting quotas. This
unit test needs to have the security group quota available for quotas to
avoid the KeyError.

Change-Id: I3214fa1e383b9520ac2bb963e41d0163d45acd62
Closes-bug: 1381073

commit_message:
Add a server console-log test with unlimited length

Now server console-log API is important for debugging gate problems
and the API is called with unlimited length for debugging. However,
there is not the API test with unlimited length.
This patch adds the test.

Change-Id: I5a35f086deddfcd54e995cb1156699592d1daea6

commit_message:
wrong logic in assertValidRoleAssignmentListResponse method

According to current logic, we always use the last of entities to
compare with ref. And, actually, we provide another method
assertRoleAssignmentInListResponse to judge whether the ref in the
list. So, the ref parameter could be removed.

Change-Id: I3f8786baa6964c0f17add2d669aa736732698ea7

commit_message:
Log translation hint for Heat.contrib

Currently, Log translation is motivated by oslo's move to prioritized
translation of strings, as documented at
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/LoggingStandards#Log_Translation

- add log translation hints for warning, error and info levels
- move from LOG.warning to LOG.warn
- remove use of % as a string formatter, use the log functionality
  instead

Partial implements blueprint log-translation-hints

Change-Id: I8dbb5430507283038939b5665d67615c46b1f72e

commit_message:
Fix options and their groups - etc/glance-api.conf

As per the docs at [0] , some of the options should have been moved
around in the etc/glance-api.conf. This patch changes the conf file to:

    1. indicate new default values
    2. change the group of some of the configs in order to adhere to
       new groups as expected by the deployer.
    3. deprecated configs have been removed or replaced with new ones.

[0] http://docs.openstack.org/trunk/config-reference/content/glance-conf-changes-master.html

Fixes bug: 1380689

Change-Id: I5b5ab96b050b502007e6660a7a613e252404d4e8

commit_message:
cluster_config argument missing in prepare()

Due to a bad merge, the prepare() call in postgresql does
not have cluster_config argument. Added that to make sure
postgres is in line with other data stores.

Change-Id: I1c3e5032447124dae47ae23ebf820fdcf8080588
Closes-Bug: #1380745

commit_message:
Add 'zvm' to the list of known hypervisor types

zvm is a hypervisor that used for IBM s390 arch and has
many years history on virtualization.
you can refer to http://www.vm.ibm.com/ for more info on it.

According to danpb's comments on
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/122200/:
FYI the list of hvtype constants is intended to define a global set of
all theoretically supported hypervisors. ie it is fine to add more
constants for hypervisors, even if Nova doesn't have a driver in-tree for it.

even if zvm is not in the nova tree now, we are trying to enhance the
code and other related stuffs such as CI test to make it acceptable to
community later. Also, zvm driver code is not in stackforge now since
we are trying to fit other criterias in order to make community accept it and
put into nova tree.

This patch simply adds zvm to the list of known hypervisor types which are
validated during scheduling given commit a4fd236.

Change-Id: I1f5b5bd2a8f082d2e945560ae82593dfd70f2a22

commit_message:
Log translation hint for Heat.engine (part1)

Currently, Log translation is motivated by oslo's move to prioritized
translation of strings, as documented at
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/LoggingStandards#Log_Translation

- add log translation hints for warning, error and info levels
- move from LOG.warning to LOG.warn
- remove use of % as a string formatter, use the log functionality
  instead

Partial implements blueprint log-translation-hints

Change-Id: Ie2f5f7b1b3ce0e6868f0c9c513adf5e870481492

commit_message:
Add expected response checks of secgroup rules

"add security group rule" API returns additional rule in its response
body but current tests don't check the response.
This patch adds some checks of the response.
In addition, this patch removes status code checks because the codes
are already checked in client side.

Change-Id: Iab4ce492c060b8a2b79a3b3d9a6d30a359f6f312
Related-Bug: #1373832

Thx nikhil. I'm not sure about devstack bug, the issue was, that  --public was suppress from the help, accepted, but no action was done in this case.
So, IMHO assign it to is_public, will "hide it" (as it suppress) from new API users, and won't break legacy API (so it's deprecated). 
Unless, we are going to completely remove --public, since I see that Devstack already support invoke with --is-public (lib/dib - line 122).'}, {'account_id': 5202, 'date': '2014-10-14 08:50:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Hi Wlodzimierz,

I do agree with Nikhil, this was the functionality already two years ago and it did not get people changing to supported syntax. If there is still someone using the non documented option They should fix it at their end.'}, {'account_id': 455, 'date': '2014-10-14 09:10:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-2

(1 comment)

Hi Wlodzimierz,

I think I agree with the others on this, that it's probably time to fully deprecate this option."}, {'account_id': 12566, 'date': '2014-10-14 10:06:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thx, Stuart
Just one more thing, there is note in v1/shell about --public:
#NOTE(bcwaldon): This will be removed once devstack is updated
# to use --is-public. 
I've checked devstack source, and in lib/dib there is usage of    --is-public. So it's should to just be ignore as it is, or remove it from v1/shell and raise error about unsupported arguments ?
cheers"}, {'account_id': 12566, 'date': '2014-10-15 05:42:38.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Issue resolved by Stuart McLaren'}]

commit_message:
support '--public' on image create

If '--public' option is used in command line, it't simply
assign to '--is-public' in fields.
Additional comment marks, what should be remove once
'--is-public' will be used.

Change-Id: I75e6b38347c7ab9507253955fb34a15dbd79d118

commit_message:
Move status check to client for "messaging" tests

This patch moves the response status code check from
tests to client side.

NOTE- Some API return different success status code on fly so
leaving those status code specific check in tests only.

Partially Implements blueprint: client-checks-success

Change-Id: Ibbab26d6a99bf67eb684cc9c3ce7845c91fa092e

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-14 08:38:15.000000000', 'message': 'Fix cleanup for EC2 test_compute_with_volumes

Volume cleanup for test_compute_with_volumes fails when volume is in
"error" state.

cleanup part destroy_volume_wait() is to delete the volume and detach
before delete if necessary.
In destroy_volume_wait(), before detaching the volume there is checks if
volume status is not "available" but that is not sufficient enough to
guarantee that volume is attached. Volume status can be "error".

When something wrong happens with Volume and Volume is in "error"
state then, detach request will through the error as mentioned in
bug# 1310896.

Logic in destroy_volume_wait should be checking of state as "in-use" before
trying to detach volume. So that if it is in "in-use" state then detach and
go for volume delete. If not in "in-use" ("available" or  "error" etc) then
only go for volume delete.

Change-Id: I1882dbba947cc294cb4fe119db50f2a1c23b75be
Related-Bug: #1310896
'}]
commit_message:
Fix cleanup for EC2 test_compute_with_volumes

Volume cleanup for test_compute_with_volumes fails when volume is in
"error" state.

cleanup part destroy_volume_wait() is to delete the volume and detach
before delete if necessary.
In destroy_volume_wait(), before detaching the volume there is checks if
volume status is not "available" but that is not sufficient enough to
guarantee that volume is attached. Volume status can be "error".

When something wrong happens with Volume and Volume is in "error"
state then, detach request will through the error as mentioned in
bug# 1310896.

Logic in destroy_volume_wait should be checking of state as "in-use" before
trying to detach volume. So that if it is in "in-use" state then detach and
go for volume delete. If not in "in-use" ("available" or  "error" etc) then
only go for volume delete.

Change-Id: I1882dbba947cc294cb4fe119db50f2a1c23b75be

Remove unnecessary explanation from emc_vmax_utils.py

Each function in emc_vmax_utils.py have explanation of
parameters/return. One function has for one unnecessary
explanation. It should be removed.

commit_message:
Fixes poor error message when deleting networks

This patch fixes the poor error message when deleting networks when
the network is being used by an active instance. The old error
message upon network deletion used to show the network UUID, which
was a little inconvenient for the end-user. So, with the help of
this patch, any error in deleting the network will show the
network name instead of network UUID.

Change-Id: I38a8a0260860383eee9d3e3b28cc4bc3ec65b255
Closes-bug: #1279485

commit_message:
Add instructions to load nbd kernel module on SUSE based systems

This solves the following issue when trying to start a new instance.

2014-10-14 13:19:32.791 20021 ERROR nova.virt.disk.mount.nbd [req-38f661b6-
b192-423b-9f41-2c28b9372af1 None] nbd module not loaded
---snap---

Change-Id: I1bc5ab6d0b40d70cb19ada660d1b0b02b7903ba3

commit_message:
Update cinder content for Juno

I updated the cinder content in the installation guide for Juno
as follows:

1) Clarified verify operation section.
2) Added instructions for attaching a volume to an instance. We
   create it, so might as well complete the process and attach
   it to an instance.

Change-Id: I658193599bb7ab91407e0180f686e2e3c6b2bf61

as can be seen at http://koji.fedoraproject.org/koji/buildinfo?buildID=581039

commit_message:
Adds status check for FloatingIP in network scenarios

Verifies FloatingIP changes status correctly on association and dis-association

Scenarios:
test_network_basic_op
test_network_advanced_server_ops

Status is verified after connectivity check and without a waiter in order to
not mask unknown races in Neutron

Changes show() to refresh() to keep consistency

Partially Implements: blueprint fip-op-status (this is a Neutron bp:
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/neutron/+spec/fip-op-status)
Partially Implements: blueprint neutron-advanced-scenarios

Change-Id: Ibd45f3092cebc8f9fd0d16a3a543c2ef72156409

commit_message:
Orchestration use stack timeout waiting for ping response

The test_server_cfn_init scenario test boots a full Fedora image,
not the cirros image which is presumably used for compute tests
where the default 120s ping timeout may be appropriate.

To ensure we don't encounter any spurious failures due to booting the
much bigger orchestration image (which is Fedora in the gate), use
the stack timeout (default 900s) to override the ping timeout for
this test.

Change-Id: I4eba18333bdaa0ef41122cda85fd3f4d91b2cf5c
Closes-Bug: #1374175

commit_message:
Neutron does not follow the RFC 3442 spec for DHCP

When setting a gateway and additional host routes in neutron subnet, the
gateway is only sent to clients via the router dhcp option, dhcp clients
conforming to rfc3442 will ignore router option if
classless-static-routes are available. This patch ensures setting both
the router option and the classless-static-routes including the gateway

Change-Id: Ia00b9385025020f848872309ae42ddac08528f53
Closes-Bug: #1317935
(cherry picked from commit ce59e63249dfcd86e782d056407e38e845cbe19c)

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-08 22:05:32.000000000', 'message': "Undo recent refactoring to generate ns_name in a single place

A recent review that merged [1] made some unfortunate trade-offs.
First, the situation was not bad to begin with.  It was a simple
concatenation of a constant with an id in only two places.  This
doesn't hit my threshold for an important refactor.  In order to
accomplish the refactoring, it introduced a new property on the
RouterInfo class (a bad example of a class that I'm working to clean
up), it then constructs a RouterInfo object for every router_id known
for the sole purpose of accessing that property.  It also wraps the
construction of a RouterInfo object because it introduces a second
place where it is constructed.  This doesn't accomplish much.  It also
gets in the way of some restructuring that we're discussing and
beginning to execute in the L3 subteam.

Please be careful not to get so eager to avoid all code duplication
that we end up making bad trade-offs.  Information hiding and code
sharing is great but it must be thought out and executed well or it
ends up building more technical debt.

I chose not to do a simple revert because the revert conflicted with
[2] which is acceptible even if a little over-zealous.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/123434
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/123435

Change-Id: Ibaf369d6ebe9285a0c845802def59bfa26ac0fd5

Be careful not to get so eager to avoid all code duplication that we

commit_message:
Avoid constructing a RouterInfo object to get namespace name

Constructing a RouterInfo object just for a string concatenation is
inefficient and adds more dependence on the class which needs
refactoring.

Change-Id: Ibaf369d6ebe9285a0c845802def59bfa26ac0fd5

It seems that default Neutron behaviour is to drop all subnets when deleting a network, and the change introduces inconsistency in how n1kv and most other plugins behave. I wonder what's the reason for the change. Is there some bug in n1kv that requires it?

We need an answer to the question to consider the change inclusion in Icehouse."}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2014-10-07 09:45:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

Hi Ihar, 

We need to explicitly trigger subnet delete for the N1k, so simply dropping the subnets from DB on network delete (which doesn't inform the plugin) isn't enough for us. That said, I've opened a bug to enhance this behavior in the future:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1379583

Thanks."}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2014-10-10 09:39:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Code-Review+2

N1kv plugin should raise an exception during network delete
if there is a subnet that is tied to that network.

Also changed the order of the assert arguments since now
it's encoraged to have <expected_value, actual_value>.

PLEASE NOTE:
This is a port to icehouse branch. It looks like there are extra test cases not relevant to the fix. However, they are need it because:
- the code I've commited in delete_network() changes the behavior and it'll fail when we try to delete a network if there are subnets on it.
- hence all the test cases which tries to delete a network and don't delete the subnets first, will fail.
- Hence ALL the test cases in test_db_plugin.py file which does that (deleting the network without deleting the subnet first), needs to be overriding and this is why you see all these test cases which seems to not be related with the diffs in n1kv_neutron_plugin.py file but they are actually very related.

Conflicts:
	neutron/tests/unit/cisco/n1kv/test_n1kv_plugin.py

commit_message:
Raise exception for network delete with subnets presents

N1kv plugin should raise an exception during network delete
if there is a subnet that is tied to that network.

Also changed the order of the assert arguments since now
it's encoraged to have <expected_value, actual_value>.

PLEASE NOTE:
This is a port to icehouse branch. It looks like there are extra test
cases not relevant to the fix. However, they are need it because:
- the code I've commited in delete_network() changes the behavior and
  it'll fail when we try to delete a network if there are subnets on it.
- hence all the test cases which tries to delete a network and don't
  delete the subnets first, will fail.
- Hence ALL the test cases in test_db_plugin.py file which does that
  (deleting the network without deleting the subnet first), needs to
  be overriding and this is why you see all these test cases which
  seems to not be related with the diffs in n1kv_neutron_plugin.py
  file but they are actually very related.

Conflicts:
	neutron/tests/unit/cisco/n1kv/test_n1kv_plugin.py

Closes-Bug: 1336107
(cherry picked from commit 89fb8b633b1ae34d0b56d73ee115462f4acc9540)
Change-Id: I92f177af0e2a2fbc460e0d668989ce590b7d1cb2

commit_message:
ofagent: Fix a possible crash in arp responder

Be careful for exceptions when feeding packet-in data,
which is generated by tenant VMs and thus can not be trusted,
to Ryu packet library.

Closes-Bug: #1365255
Change-Id: Ia8bacfb55def563a1b23a47709ae72bd4fce0fce

commit_message:
Add InvalidIpForNetworkClient exception

When posting an 'attach interface' request to Nova with an invalid
ip for defined network, Nova returns an HTTP 500 error. In fact,
Neutron returns 'InvalidInput' error, but Neutron client is not able
to translate this error to a specific exception. So that a general
'BadRequest' exception is thrown. Neutron client and Nova need a more
specific Neutron error type, in order to address and translate the
error in to a proper Nova exception.

Change-Id: Idd964c33476d7559f642287d577f8a6122d7674c
Partial-Bug: 1369871

commit_message:
Security Group rule validation for ICMP rules

Currently there is no validation in Security Group rules
when an ICMP rule is added with icmp code alone. A rule
is getting added but there is a mismatch between SG rules
and the corresponding iptables rule that is added.
This patch does the necessary validation on the input.

Closes-Bug: #1301838
Change-Id: I510abac4c426f68ea57c99a5fef3da4058f88797
(cherry picked from commit 7607e3da884551e5c4cfe49de390afbddbb2a9b3)

commit_message:
Log translation hint for Heat.engine (part3)

Currently, Log translation is motivated by oslo's move to prioritized
translation of strings, as documented at
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/LoggingStandards#Log_Translation
- add log translation hints for warning, error and info levels
- move from LOG.warning to LOG.warn
- remove use of % as a string formatter, use the log functionality
  instead
Partial implements blueprint log-translation-hints

Change-Id: Ib91983e6e61b4d6ddbbed0f95dc98cbde1d4f673

commit_message:
Log translation hint for Heat.engine (part2)

Currently, Log translation is motivated by oslo's move to prioritized
translation of strings, as documented at
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/LoggingStandards#Log_Translation
- add log translation hints for warning, error and info levels
- move from LOG.warning to LOG.warn
- remove use of % as a string formatter, use the log functionality
  instead
Partial implements blueprint log-translation-hints

Change-Id: Ib943d41e7c1931af6d84e69ee3bc086221fc9725

commit_message:
Adding tests for sahara client exeptions

Currently sahara client has not any tests for common methods. This patch
adds missed tests and also sets exceptions_module variable.

Closes-bug: #1380563

[{'created': '2014-10-13 19:23:43.000000000', 'message': 'Make Rackspace Cloud DNS TTL constraints match API

The Rackspace Cloud DNS TTLs have a minimum constraint of 301, but,
according to the API docs, the minimum is "300 seconds or more".

Change-Id: I924889f859de4226d5e7517576e40d1fdbba3064
Closes-Bug: #1380755
'}]
commit_message:
Make Rackspace Cloud DNS TTL constraints match API

The Rackspace Cloud DNS TTLs have a minimum constraint of 301, but,
according to the API docs, the minimum is "300 seconds or more".

Change-Id: I924889f859de4226d5e7517576e40d1fdbba3064
Closes-Bug: #1380755

subject: Clarify snapshot deletion methods

This is still backwards.

handle_snapshot_delete doesn't delete a snapshot, it does a snapshot-delete (i.e. stores a snapshot and then deletes the original). It doesn't really make sense to change the name because "Snapshot" is baked in as the deletion policy in both HOT and CFN. In any case, changing the name would gratuitously break existing plugins and is therefore Not Cool.

handle_delete_snapshot deletes an existing snapshot (it's part of Thomas's new feature to snapshot the whole stack). Arguably it could be named something different (like handle_delete_backup), although snapshot is *also* the name used in the UI here. At a minimum we'd have to backport the change to Juno to avoid having two plugin formats out there.

At this point I'm inclined to just leave it how it is.'}, {'account_id': 6577, 'date': '2014-10-03 13:10:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

Zane, I understand your points about leaving it without changes. (We ca not re-write API in one moment and every day and I understand that it's already fixed names). In the same time I still think that we could not save this variant. 

As minimum input, I suppose, we should add some explanation in documentation, because we use Snapshot word in both cases:

- as deletion policy 
- to snapshot whole stack

These features are not related between each other and it's very confusing. The first idea when you choose Deletion policy equal Snapshot you expect, that something happens (will be deleted) with snapshot (which you create via handle_create_snapshot), but it's not that we have in reality :(.

There are two similar and confused things presented in code:
'handle_delete_snapshot' and 'handle_snapshot_delete'. They have
different aims and have similar names. This patch solves mentioned issue
via follow changes:
 - prefix was replaced on suffix to make function name consistent:
   'handle_<action>_<some_specific_object>'.
 - Confusing 'handle_snapshot_delete' is renamed to
   'handle_delete_backup'. It is used for deletion when deletion policy
   is set in Snapshot state.
 - 'action_handler_task' is used in delete_snapshot function.
 - There are some corresponding changes in documentation.

Change-Id: I88997df97956cc36b071f116dd678df109e0f2de

commit_message:
Clarify snapshot deletion methods

There are two similar and confused things presented in code:
'handle_delete_snapshot' and 'handle_snapshot_delete'. In this patch
documenatation is updated to clarify current differences between this
two features.

Change-Id: I88997df97956cc36b071f116dd678df109e0f2de

commit_message:
Remove deprecated function i18n.install('heat')

Since i18n.install() is deprecated, remove it from heat codes and
import i18n._() to where it needed.

blueprint oslo-i18n
Change-Id: Icefada18b5a33112b425cd90d31d3a6a5f06188a
(cherry picked from commit 11c1b62052e8ffe3c1af320aaced645a19868dff)

[{'created': '2014-10-14 20:22:07.000000000', 'message': "Add tox genconfig target

It's easy to get a false config generated using a local (non venv)
environment to run generate_sample.sh, so this makes it easier to
run the config generator in a venv for consistent results which
should match what's done in the gate.

Possibly in future we could consider removing the static conf.sample
like some other projects have already done and just documenting
this as the method to generate the sample.

Change-Id: I92964d75e0adf73eb0935c2052adf344f15bfe95
"}]
commit_message:
Add tox genconfig target

It's easy to get a false config generated using a local (non venv)
environment to run generate_sample.sh, so this makes it easier to
run the config generator in a venv for consistent results which
should match what's done in the gate.

Possibly in future we could consider removing the static conf.sample
like some other projects have already done and just documenting
this as the method to generate the sample.

Change-Id: I92964d75e0adf73eb0935c2052adf344f15bfe95

commit_message:
Fix E131 PEP8 errors

Fixes files with the following error:

    E131 continuation line unaligned for hanging indent

and enables the check in tox.ini.

Also enables the E113 check (unexpected indentation) since it seems
that was fixed coincidentally with other previous changes.

Change-Id: I9270e5df257e12dc903689d8eb6fb03be01c034b

commit_message:
Improve share list API filtering

1) Added new params for filtering by:
- share network
- snapshot
- volume type
- host
- limit and offset a la pagination
- project id (useful with '--all-tenants')
- metadata*
- extra-specs*
- direction (asc, desc)*
- key of share*

* requires server-side update

2) Added aliases for params, mostly in perspective to avoid mess of underscore
and dash symbols.

3) Updated utils.print_list func to print results as is without reordering.

Implements  blueprint improve-share-list-filtering

Change-Id: I6fe92c5242f18c900e109271f9182bd5ed287b25

commit_message:
Export cinder volumes only if the status is 'in-use'

Currently, cinder volumes are exported both 'in-use' and 'available'
after restarting cinder-volume service.
This behavior was introduced following commit.

  commit ffefe18334a9456250e1b6ff88b7b47fb366f374
  Author: Zhiteng Huang <zhithuang@ebaysf.com>
  Date: Sat Aug 23 18:32:57 2014 +0000

If the volumes are attached to nova instances, they should be exported
via tgtd after restarting cinder-volume.
But the volumes which are not attached to instances must not be exported
because everyone can connect these volumes.

This patch changes volume export behavior that exports a volume only if
the volume status is 'in-use'.

Change-Id: I4c598c240b9290c81bd8001e5a0720c8c329aeb9
Signed-off-by: Mitsuhiro Tanino <mitsuhiro.tanino@hds.com>
Closes-bug: #1381106
(cherry picked from commit e2f28b967910625432be0eab6a851adf53ac58ea)

subject: Fixes Keystone Public URL
messages:
[{'account_id': 6836, 'date': '2014-10-14 18:41:01.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-14 18:46:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-kolla-bashate http://logs.openstack.org/02/128402/1/check/gate-kolla-bashate/92261ba : FAILURE in 3s (non-voting)
- gate-kolla-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/02/128402/1/check/gate-kolla-pep8/ceb6f56 : SUCCESS in 13s'}, {'account_id': 8745, 'date': '2014-10-14 18:58:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I'm still not convinced this is the right change.

(a) I don't think most of the services actually utilize the service catalog; it is primarily an end-user tool.

(b) Any service catalog entries we expect to be useful will need to be accessible from outside kubernetes.  While we don't have a model for this yet, I'm pretty sure that it will involve passing in a public ip address when creating the pod.

This suggests that we should continue using PUBLIC_IP in the publicurl endpoint.  Can you show me an example of where this is causing problems right now?"}, {'account_id': 2834, 'date': '2014-10-14 22:23:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I think we should accept for milestone #1 to use OpenStack, you must be logged into one of the k8s minions.  We have no solution for accessing OpenStack on the minions external to the k8s cluster.  I'm not certain how this can be fixed.

If PUBLIC_IP is causing problems in this use case, (logged into minions) then we should take a look at fixing it.

Also the catalog is used extensively by every client API so we need to make sure we have a working catalog."}, {'account_id': 6836, 'date': '2014-10-15 00:53:06.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Not needed. publicurl should use PUBLIC_IP. Had issues with linkmanager not connecteing 10.251.x.x kube host networks over vxlan tunnels.'}]

commit_message:
Fixes Keystone Public URL

Previously, the container IP was being used to create the Keystone
publicurl. This causes OS services that reside on other hosts to
fail communicating with Keystone when using the publicurl.

Change-Id: I7376e6264734cd75155a6c9a0103f5234b288c44

commit_message:
cluster_config argument missing in prepare()

Due to a bad merge, the prepare() call in postgresql does
not have cluster_config argument. Added that to make sure
postgres is in line with other data stores.

Change-Id: I1c3e5032447124dae47ae23ebf820fdcf8080588
Closes-Bug: #1380745

[{'created': '2014-09-30 21:41:24.000000000', 'message': 'Ignore errors when deleting non-existing vifs

If an instance fails during its network creation (for example
if the network-vif-plugged event doesn't arrive in time) a
subsequent delete will also fail when it tries to delete the
vif, leaving the instance in a Error(deleting) state.

This can be avoided by including the "--if-exists" option to
the ovs-vsctl command so that the command doesn't fail if the
vif doesn't exist.

Change-Id: Ic613c9d6e0619f51fcd931e62f6d6bce404ebe81
Closes-bug: #1308544
(cherry picked from commit 476dc5efcdb11c9859b062dc69a8c205e69be861)
'}]
commit_message:
Ignore errors when deleting non-existing vifs

If an instance fails during its network creation (for example
if the network-vif-plugged event doesn't arrive in time) a
subsequent delete will also fail when it tries to delete the
vif, leaving the instance in a Error(deleting) state.

This can be avoided by including the "--if-exists" option to
the ovs-vsctl command so that the command doesn't fail if the
vif doesn't exist.

Change-Id: Ic613c9d6e0619f51fcd931e62f6d6bce404ebe81
Closes-bug: #1308544
(cherry picked from commit 476dc5efcdb11c9859b062dc69a8c205e69be861)

commit_message:
Fixes missing ec2 api address disassociate error on failure

Fixes ec2 api address disassociate so that the ec2 error
InvalidAssociationID.NotFound is returned when it is passed an
invalid association rather than returning success. Note this is
slightly different than the original bug report but the type
of failure has changed since the bug was originally filed.

Change-Id: I10034a2fed62d4e93bc384aef3ff594b66e285f2
Closes-Bug: 1179816
(cherry picked from commit 00d8c334bbfaef3ffec4b04b494e609740b96253)

commit_message:
[Sahara] style the template parameter configuration filter

Create Cluster Template's parameter tabs  have a filter field
that allows you to filter on the configuration options.
This should have the Bootstrap 3 styling like the other filter
fields in Horizon.

Change-Id: Iac3e53b8e3b33b7b6783a601468cc4f2b3f694b9
Closes-Bug: #1380825

commit_message:
Move javelin execution into a run_javelin()

Wraps execution of javelin in run_javelin() which takes care of
config initialization and determining whether or not javelin should
even be run.  This fixes a new bug where javelin resources are being
destroyed when RUN_JAVELIN=False.

Change-Id: Id5c1ee9553624c4a3e1ae2db667df1e6fce4fcaf

commit_message:
Fix options and their groups - etc/glance-api.conf

As per the docs at [0] , some of the options should have been moved
around in the etc/glance-api.conf. This patch changes the conf file to:

    1. indicate new default values
    2. change the group of some of the configs in order to adhere to
       new groups as expected by the deployer.
    3. deprecated configs have been removed or replaced with new ones.

[0] http://docs.openstack.org/trunk/config-reference/content/glance-conf-changes-master.html

Fixes bug: 1380689

Change-Id: I5b5ab96b050b502007e6660a7a613e252404d4e8

commit_message:
VMware: validate that VM exists on backend prior to deletion

Attempting to delete an instance that does not exist on the backend
throws an exception (for example UnregisterVM may return this when
running the CI).

Fixes: bug #1300788

(cherry picked from commit 98fb5e56ef96c0c6a8754276e5f8c9c0b7e50fed)

Change-Id: I1b95caec2dad6580db576aa6f80f47913b7c066e

'}, {'created': '2014-10-07 20:43:06.000000000', 'message': 'Introduce the connection class

The connection class can be made with a transport and/or authenticator
that was already constructed or it can be made with nothing.  The
create method will create a transport, authenticator and session if
they are needed.  The normal use case would look something like:

commit_message:
Introduce the connection class

The connection class can be made with a transport and/or authenticator
that was already constructed or it can be made with nothing.  The
create method will create a transport, authenticator and session if
they are needed.  The normal use case would look something like:

    conn = connection.Connection(**auth_args)

Change-Id: I27573bce799d9992748967b5ea1b575139a75853

commit_message:
Logging audit for guestagent/mongodb

Adjust logging to conform to logging standards.
Cleaned up a few messages that were unclear and changed several
LOG.info messages to LOG.debug.

Also fixed a pattern of exception handlers using LOG.error
merely to log the exception (instead of LOG.exception)

Change-Id: I3bd544b761b449d1181792ff498f9c171331df16
Partial-Bug: #1324206

commit_message:
Revert "Relocate volume to compliant datastore"

Commit 4be8913520f5e9fe4109ade101da9509e4a83360 introduced a regression
which causes failures during cinder volume re-attach. This patch reverts
commit 4be8913520f5e9fe4109ade101da9509e4a83360 as an immediate fix.

Closes-Bug: #1379830
Change-Id: I5dfbd45533489c3c81db8d256bbfd2f85614a357
(cherry picked from commit 48cb82971e0418f9a629e2b39d0433dc2c0e6919)

commit_message:
Adjust authentication.rst doc to reference "identity_uri"

The "auth_port", "auth_host", and "auth_protocol" variables were
deprecated in favour of a single "identity_uri" variable.

* Adjust authentication.rst doc to reference "identity_uri"

Change-Id: I48de53f21b8d767b276858ed274066015d765f0e
Closes-Bug: #1361613

Only suggestions/questions, otherwise it looks nice for me.

Calls just to "get_admin_creds()" without args are used,
though msg's for exceptions are set to "<Some specific> admin is missing".
Maybe it would be better to fake the concept of get_admin_creds(['volume', 'compute', ...]) then?

In lot of cases InvalidConfiguration is raised, though for ex. in api.compute.base
skipException is used instead when there is no admin.
This seems little bit inconsistent - not clear to me on first look what to expect.
I would suggest to unify the exception(s) used in all cases,

commit_message:
Add Credentials Provider factory

Add a method to select the appropriate credentials provider based
on configuration, and replace all the flow branches based on
allow_tenant_isolation to use the factory.

This also includes handling NotImplemented exceptions on admin creds
for scenarios tests which is a new potential condition by using the
factory.

Partially-implements bp:test-accounts

Change-Id: I280f2b1659c593e14ab9213a161b55bcfc08fa5c

commit_message:
Debian: update libvirtd init script path

Lately [1], Debian packaging changed to use /etc/default/libvirtd instead of
/etc/default/libvirt-bin (probably to align with systemd, since in Red
Hat it's /etc/sysconfig/libvirtd).

This patch aims to modifify nova::migration::libvirt to build the right
init script path from a param in nova::compute::libvirt
(libvirt_service_name).

[1] http://anonscm.debian.org/cgit/pkg-libvirt/libvirt.git/commit/debian/libvirt-bin.maintscript?id=28dd3618a9a2a8f769d1fa12c28647c4599d9e8e

Change-Id: I7483efe644d301c2646e4063fe7f1aef3e83cb6b
Closes-bug: #1381172

commit_message:
Update delete config param test to be idempotent

Added configuration parameter create call on the integration test
"test_delete_configuration_parameter_with_mgmt_api". Also added
assert to confirm the new parameter was created before deletion.
Previously the test would delete the 'connect_timeout' parameter.
When the test would be run for a second time it would throw an
error that the parameter could not be found.

Change-Id: Ie794d0159ba4e5fd5e335e8f6ff8749d92682650
Closes-Bug: 1379083

commit_message:
Preserve exit value when leaving cleanup trap

If we entered the cleanup trap due to exit with an error code we should
exit dib with an error code.

Change-Id: Iee1a05668b3239113fb91a2da0d9a66d7de4db6b

commit_message:
Correct node CREATION_ATTRIBUTE "uuid"

Ironic's REST API allows a client to supply a UUID when registering a node.
However, the client was incorrectly passing this value as the "node_id"
property, rather than the "uuid" property, resulting in the API service
ignoring the parameter and generating a new UUID anyway.

This corrects the behavior by passing the appropriately named parameter
if the user specified a UUID when registering a new node.

Closes-bug: #1381203
Change-Id: I23ebbf20d836f0afc507be5c9dbbe1d759a3cddb

commit_message:
HP 3PAR: Don't ignore extra-specs snap_cpg when missing cpg

When snap_cpg is specified in extra-specs, it should be used.
For some reason, it was being ignored when extra-specs did not
also specify a user cpg.

When using a volume-type, the snapCPG should come from (in this order
of preference):
1. extra specs snap_cpg,
2. extra specs cpg,
3. config hp3par_cpg_snap,
4. config hp3par_cpg.

Change-Id: I649e3dc49f7775a8071229fc315f0ee5f23aa833
Closes-Bug: 1368972

model update when our volume-type CPG is used
instead of the scheduler selected CPG.

new return of (boolean, model_update).  This new
return is like the other APIs and is needed for
us to correct the host after some retypes.

commit_message:
3PAR with pool-aware-cinder-scheduler

HP 3PAR support for the pool-aware scheduler.
Adds support for a list of CPGs (pools).  Uses
model update when our volume-type CPG is used
instead of the scheduler selected CPG.

In cinder.conf, hp3par_cpg now accepts a list of CPGs.

DocImpact
Implements: blueprint pool-aware-cinder-scheduler-hp3par
Change-Id: I74ef0af5390311eb1a529e0d5d4875c4f7d04156

commit_message:
Verify network interfaces are in requested order

There is no Tempest test verifying that the order of multiple networks passed
to an instance during its creation is preserved within the instance
(https://review.openstack.org/#/c/85711/). This change introduces a new test
in test_create_server to verify this feature.

Change-Id: I3622b9e8dfbbf73eb9a0a69d2094b75e4934fe17

commit_message:
Publish devstack documents

Publish devstack documents in a post job on
docs.openstack.org/developer/devstack

Also, add a check job (non-voting for now).

We need extra jobs since devstack does not support the
build_sphinx target.

This depends on these two patches for devstack:
* https://review.openstack.org/126714
* https://review.openstack.org/126720

Change-Id: I68f85e13848af0bc25a101ae7474ce9fb240393f

I am a bit confused with this patch.

After applying this patch, a title and a content of a selected tab are separated by a line, but titles of hidden tabs are not separated with a content of the selected tab. I think the titles of hidden tabs and the content of the selected tab are completely unrelated, so the previous (= current) version sounds more reasonable to me. The separation of a title and a content of the selected tab looks a good direction to me too, but I am afraid we are introducing another type of confusion.

In my understanding, this proposal comes from UX community, so I would like to see a reply from UX point of view.'}, {'account_id': 7699, 'date': '2014-10-03 11:06:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

See my previous comment. Plus:

The sub-navigation is more related to the header if we talk about the hierarchy. 

Example:
I am in the Instance Detail view. There might be various sub-sections: Overview, Monitoring, Log, Console,... and I am currently seeing Monitoring section. In order to know where I am, I need to know that I am in Compute > Instances > Instance Detail > Monitoring. Following the information flow, I see Compute and Instances in the left nav since they are main navigation items for me. To keep going, I see Instance detail info from the header of the page and that I am in Monitoring is right underneath.

How I am perceiving the information is from the top to bottom. It is not the opposite way that I have content and from that I am searching for the header to know where I am. and if so, I need to know Instance Detail > Monitoring. If Monitoring label is separated from the header and related to the content, it is not enough info - it should be always attached to the heading.

So far there are both reactions - there are lovers and there are haters.

We should approach this type of navigation as sub-navigation and not tabs. In order to make the look less heavy I used only lines to separate header from the content. But if it would be a problem, we will have to use navigation bar with some background to separate the navigation items from the content if there would be a significant amount of users who are confused.'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2014-10-04 14:06:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

Thanks Jaromir for the explanation. I don’t necessarily oppose the general direction, but just moving a separation line of the selected tab does not solve the problem. In my case, when I would like to perceiving the whole information I do the same way as you described (i.e., Compute > Instances > Instance Detail > Log). However, when I am looking at the instance detail and just want to move another tab, I look for a tab title by moving my eye from the content. In this case, I look for a tab title which is not separated from the content page. This is similar to what most browsers do (including Chorme or Firefox). There is no separation line or similar thing between a tab title and a page content.

My point is we need to make titles of *unselected* tabs more clearly separated from both a title of a page and a content of a selected tab. If we go to this direction, at least I think we need to add separation lines to the bottom of title of unselected tabs for better separation.

The current proposed solution provides a clear separation from a title of a page, but on the other hand it loses a separation from a page content. Assume a case there are only two tabs. I can’t know which tab is selected unless I check which tab title can be clicked and it is so frustrated to me. From this reason, this change will bring a confusion for existing Horizon users even though this change provides a good user experience for *new* users. We should take into account a case of upgrading.

Finally, did you see Hypervisor panel? At least I don’t think it is an improvement. Do you think it is less confusing?'}, {'account_id': 9317, 'date': '2014-10-06 09:08:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12: Patch Set 11 was rebased'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-06 10:12:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12: Verified+1

Yes, I agree that tabs in browsers are having this type of interaction. Though it is a bit different context.

Anyway, I'd love to move us forward and not get stuck. I think the point of argument here is graphical design, which we can try to improve:
people.redhat.com/~jcoufal/openstack/horizon/details/2014-10-06_details.pdf

See pages 4 and 5. As for me, I would love to go forward with the design on p4 - it is more clean and "air-y". If more people thinks that it is confusing and we need better separation of sub-navigation and content, we can go with the design of p5 (I'd say it's still acceptable, though I personally don't like it that much).

As for Hypervisor page - there is different problem. Since you have content (graphs) and then tabbed table (where the regular tabs definitely make sense).

We need to separate from sub-navigation and tabbed content. The change proposed in this patch is concerning sub-navigation enhancements only.

If we need tabbed tables (or widgets), we should design for them but let's focus first on this first step and improvement.

Hypervisor view should be fixed in a way that it is re-done for sub-navigation or it stays as it is and we design for tabbed tables. Either way is fine with me but we can combine them.

-- Jarda'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2014-10-06 13:33:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12: -Code-Review

Thanks Jaromir again. Tab styling like pp.4-5 looks clear to me. We are now in the beginning of the new development cycle and I believe it is a good start line. If we have good progresses in Kilo, I have no concern. My only concern on this patch is that the proposed tab styling is potentially confusing for users who use the current design if we have slow progress in Kilo. I agree it is not good to stuck here of course, and I remove my -1. I hope we have good progress in early Kilo.'}, {'account_id': 7699, 'date': '2014-10-06 13:36:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12:

commit_message:
Fix doc build warnings so docs build clean

Tried for as minimal changes as possible.

example warning is:
manila/share/drivers/service_instance.py:docstring of
manila.share.drivers.service_instance.ServiceInstanceManager:5: ERROR: Unexpected indentation.

Change-Id: Ic3cce38ac555deaac4b80bc5eb0d8484bc92364f
Closes-Bug: 1379935

commit_message:
Cluster Error On Missing Volume Sizes Unoptimal

if the volume size is omitted on an instance, and volume_support
is true, then the error should indicate that the volume size
is missing, vs. stating that the volume sizes don't match.

Change-Id: I40c807313eaed4fb2f433da1c8a80089e01756fa
Closes-Bug: #1369001

commit_message:
Sync process utils from oslo

This patch backports the missing change to fix ssh_execute password leak

------------------------------------------------
The sync pulls in the following changes:

105169f8 - Mask passwords in exceptions and error messages (SSH)
-----------------------------------------------

Closes-Bug: 1377981

commit_message:
Fix volume name support of unmanage and replication commands

Volume not found error occurs when running these commands via cinderclient
with volume name as an argument.
unmanage, replication-promote, replication-reenable

However in their help text, it is described that Name and ID are supported.
Therefore, this patch fixes volume name support to their argument.

Closes-bug: #1374211
Change-Id: I8b90523d8e79a65eb27ff4e99820e8cb3feb3120

commit_message:
Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This causes docs jobs to fail because we error out on warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910

commit_message:
Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910

commit_message:
Use jsonutils from oslo.serialization

Now that jsonutils has been moved to its own library from
oslo-incubator, the code in nova/openstack/common/jsonutils.py is no
longer needed. All references to that module have been updated to import
the oslo.serialization version instead, and the order of the import
statements has been fixed.

Change-Id: I25bcaef28455b7616cee3bb2b969911ef74b77b5

commit_message:
Move the doc paths to match other repos

In order to build in the Infra system, we'd like to be able to reuse the
existing doc build macros. To support that, move docs/source to
doc/source and docs/html to doc/build/html.

Change-Id: Ibd8e8e82e54c69b182120df67e6ec6908fed2908

commit_message:
Update heat content for Juno

I updated the heat content in the installation guide for Juno
as follows:

1) Restructured procedures to match other chapters.
2) Removed MySQL references.
3) Added step to load admin credentials prior to keystone
   steps.
4) Added region to endpoints.
5) Added note about verbose mode.
6) Explictly installed python-heatclient package.
7) Removed 'logdir' workaround for Ubuntu.
8) Changed RHEL/CentOS/Fedora to use systemd init scripts.
9) Changed openSUSE to use systemd init scripts.
10) Fixed other minor issues.

I tested the contents of this patch on RHEL, CentOS, Fedora,
and Ubuntu.

Change-Id: Ia35dd4adfd89c34a2a1574510a430737c938a159

commit_message:
Bump up taskflow to its newest version

Taskflow 0.5 was released, it was mainly a minor bug fix release
and requirements and documentation update release so it'd be nice
to have it as useable for the various using projects.

Release announce/docs @ https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/TaskFlow-0.5

commit_message:
nova-compute-service doesn't expose a port

AFAIK the service files are only for services with ports exposed.  Since
nova-compute doesn't expose a port, kubecfg returns an error when attempting
to register it:

F1014 17:06:34.329482 32317 kubecfg.go:395] Got request error:
service "novacompute" is invalid: port: invalid value '0'

Change-Id: I4d9f8d50d538f42d520f3d9437ab32aa6a226d2b

commit_message:
add better validation checks (part 1)

This patch adds a script for validating YAML files, and replaces the
existing JSON checks with one largely identical to the YAML check.

This also provides a script that can be installed as a pre-commit hook
that will perform this checks when you commit changes.  You can install
the hook by running tools/pre-commit-hook --install.

Change-Id: Ib4742a9db062362cfa61d669c691151bc1ca376c

commit_message:
Nova-controller needs a start script

The nova-controller is going to make all the configurations
so it needs a script to setup nova.conf. The config data is
stored locally in nova.conf and will be read in and executed by line.

Change-Id: Id501212671201ca68cd08018ce024db284dd8c54

commit_message:
Encode middleware error message as bytes

On py3 the middleware message needs to be passed as bytes instead of
string. Since on py2 str.encode() doesn't do anything it doesn't change
the behavior there.

Change-Id: Ie593e8659be736aa4d85ca2a47ae2a30db446f84
Closes-Bug: 1372484

commit_message:
Nailgun/fuel-agent integration

Added provision_metadata JSON field into release model.
This field is necessary to make nailgun able to provide
fuel-agent with the information about which image to download,
what it's format, etc. This field also contains information
about which provisioning method to use (cobbler or image).

Change-Id: I0f15b0e713d7ec97e67d26f4eba3cd76bdc18806

[{'created': '2014-09-29 20:28:20.000000000', 'message': 'Permit non-loopback guest access to Rabbit

Recent versions of RabbitMQ have defaulted to only permitting the
guest user to access over a loopback interface. To allow the guest
user to connect from a remote host set the loopback_users
configuration as shown in http://www.rabbitmq.com/access-control.html

Change-Id: Ibe953c4c88ce4632b2dd099f013eda3fc451c20f
'}]
commit_message:
Permit non-loopback guest access to Rabbit

Recent versions of RabbitMQ have defaulted to only permitting the
guest user to access over a loopback interface. To allow the guest
user to connect from a remote host set the loopback_users
configuration as shown in http://www.rabbitmq.com/access-control.html

Change-Id: Ibe953c4c88ce4632b2dd099f013eda3fc451c20f

commit_message:
VMware: mark virtual machines as 'belonging' to OpenStack

This patch registers an extension in vCenter that indicates that the
VM's that are run from OpenStack will belong to OpenStack.

If an administrator tries to update the VM via vCenter then they will
get the following message:

"Solution OpenStack manages the selected virtual machine. You should
not modify the virtual machine directly. Use the management console of
the solution to make changes. Do you want to proceed?"

The extension will be called 'org.openstack.compute'. This will make use
of a type called 'instance'.

Closes-bug: #1366506

Change-Id: I1046576c448704841ae8e1800b8390e947b0d457

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Rename cli variable in ironic driver

Code in ironic driver used "icli" as variable name to reference to
ironic client instance. It has been renamed to "ironicclient" to make
the code clearer.

Change-Id: Ic9e314e882f5e5e305a5ea84f7c2f102f91140dd
Closes-Bug: #1365228

commit_message:
Remove @author tags from copyright statements

We have git to track the authorship of files. It is not necessary to use
the @author tags in the copyright statements.

Change-Id: I67163ffe46540423ca1f5584881d7c2db47fe276

commit_message:
Switch to nova's jsonutils in oslo.serialization

Very simple import change in each file, just touches a
whole lot of files. jsonutils has graduated into a stand alone
library and has been removed from the oslo-incubator repository.
We should be using the library for all projects.

Change-Id: I09d780a47d377871f357654603ee4b0fa0169d66

commit_message:
Run telemetry in javelin if resources.yaml says so

In previous code telemetry checks were always run (if there
were servers to check). If the environment did not have ceilometer
services this would fail.

check_telemetry now checks that there is a true value on the
'telemetry' key in resources.yaml. No configuration is required for
the telemetry checks, so only a key with a value is required.

Change-Id: I84e0f5938ec808537043dba29a896f991779b04c

commit_message:
Adds TestSecurityGroupsBasicOps created VM's security_groups check

In nova.compute.manager.ComputeManager._build_instance, there is the
following code:
if request_spec and self.is_neutron_security_groups:
    security_groups = request_spec.get('security_group')
else:
    security_groups = []

Which will verify this from
nova.network.security_group.openstack_driver:
def is_neutron_security_groups():
    return CONF.security_group_api.lower() in ('neutron', 'quantum')

This basically means that if the Nova compute node's nova.conf
does not contain security_group_api=neutron, the created VMs
security_groups will be [], which later will be default.

This commit checks the created VM's security_groups, this way
it makes sure that the created security group rules will be
applied to the VM.

Closes-Bug: #1364015

Change-Id: I444c128b6be01e29dd95c8727b7fb676e3dc4eed

commit_message:
Forbid update of HA property of routers

While the HA property is update-able, and resulting router-get
invocations suggest that the router is HA, the migration
itself fails on the agent. This is deceiving and confusing
and should be blocked until the migration itself is fixed
in a future patch.

Change-Id: I4171ab481e3943e0110bd9a300d965bbebe44871
Related-Bug: #1365426
Closes-Bug: #1378525
(cherry picked from commit 1fd7dd99ca7e5e9736200360aa354cada7fb43ff)

commit_message:
Improvements for task plot2html

CLI command `task plot2html' is renamed to `task report',
however old name is still available for compatibility.

HTML output of benchmark results is reworked:
     * scenario select dropdown is changed to aside menu,
       with scenarios methods grouped by classes
     * initially select scenario from URL hash
     * scenario results are divided into tabs
     * new layout and styling, from bootstrap framework
     * jQuery is removed
     * AngularJS is used for rendering all the data

Change-Id: I00db7016900952f397681045ff99d07a0714fafe

commit_message:
Added missing template tests and checked existing ones (III)

Covers all template plugins except midonet and metaplugin
(see https://bugs.launchpad.net/bugs/1380243). Obvious mistakes
have been corrected in some of the templates (trailing
whitespaces, cut&pasted attribute names, instance variables
instead of block variables and so on).

Change-Id: I2302cd4f0ef29be4f1d783de930af2abbf7c1a15
Closes-Bug: #1328999
Implements: blueprint add-template-tests

commit_message:
Add test to verify endpoints can be configured

This patch updates the test suite to test that each endpoint can be
configured independently of each other to ensure that the endpoints
do not regress to multiple endpoints being configured by a single
chef attribute.

Change-Id: I6ebd78223bc580730e2d902141b5f84486998df7
Closes-Bug: #1356732

commit_message:
add doc8 validation

doc8 is similar to flake8, but for documentation: it's an opinionated
style checker.

  https://github.com/stackforge/doc8

This patch also fixes two violations, regarding maximum line length and
trailing whitespace.

Change-Id: Icdbd360cea149f1af72243a59efedaed504ff336

commit_message:
Name pipelines in zuul gerrit comments

When zuul comments on gerrit changes prefix the messages with the name
of the pipeline that generated this comment. This will allow other
tooling to know which pipeline generated a comment.

Change-Id: I252ae31e7a4cb919e3c98c35591147cc96cfc3cc

commit_message:
Updated policy module from oslo-incubator

This is to avoid policy module dependency on jsonutils that are now
moved to oslo.serialization.

Dropped Neutron specific policy_file option since now it's defined in
oslo-incubator policy module.

The following changes are included:

6c706c5 Delete graduated serialization files
5d40e14 Remove code that moved to oslo.i18n
1b44601 Allow dictionary lookup in credentials with dot notation
aebb58f Fix typo to show correct log message
bb410d9 Use MultiStrOpt for policy_dirs
33f44bf Add support for policy configration directories
2b966f9 Fix deletion of cached file for policy enforcer
238e601 Make policy debug logging less verbose
fe3389e Improve help strings
15722f1 Adds a flag to determine whether to reload the rules in policy
5d1f15a Documenting policy.json syntax
fcf517d Update oslo log messages with translation domains
e038d89 Fix policy tests for parallel testing
0da5de6 Allow policy.json resource vs constant check
e4b2334 Replaces use of urlutils with six in policy module
8b2b0b7 Use hacking import_exceptions for gettextutils._
0d8f18b Use urlutils functions instead of urllib/urllib2
12bcdb7 Remove vim header
9ef9fec Use six.string_type instead of basestring
4bfb7a2 Apply six for metaclass
1538c80 ConfigFileNotFoundError with proper argument
33533b0 Keystone user can't perform revoke_token
64bb5e2 Fix wrong argument in openstack common policy
b7edc99 Fix missing argument bug in oslo common policy
3626b6d Fix policy default_rule issue
7bf8ee9 Allow use of hacking 0.6.0 and enable new checks
e4ac367 Fix missing argument bug in oslo common policy
1a2df89 Enable H302 hacking check
7119e29 Enable hacking H404 test.
6d27681 Enable H306 hacking check.
1091b4f Reduce duplicated code related to policies

Change-Id: I24c3bc4c1e844f1a455965bf39342cd34e58fff9

Yongli He, thank you for your patch! Syncing with the upstream is definitely what we need.

However, I'd like to propose a little different approach which I think will make the stuff easier and more clear. So there are the next steps:

1. Modify our policy.json to something like:

    {
        "admin": "role:admin or role:administrator",
        "admin_api": "is_admin:True",
        "public_api": "is_public_api:True",
        "trusted_call": "rule:admin_api or rule:public_api",
        "default": "rule:trusted_call"
    }

2. In ironic.common.policy convert the ENFORCER to be a singleton and remove all other functions from that module.

3. In ironic.api.hooks.AdminAuthHook get use of the new Enforcer features:

        enforcer = policy.get_enforcer()
        enforcer.enforce('trusted_call', ctx.to_dict(), ctx.to_dict(),
                         do_rise=True, exc=exc.HTTPForbidden)

4. Update some fixtures in tests to make use of the new code.


IMO, this is simpler and requires less code in Ironic itself. What do the other folks think?'}, {'account_id': 10239, 'date': '2014-08-04 12:20:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

@Roman your proposal looks good to me actually. As I understand that way we'll use much more Oslo code and much less our self-written, right?"}, {'account_id': 6623, 'date': '2014-08-04 12:23:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

commit_message:
Rewrite ironic policy to use the new changes of common policy

The oslo has rewritten the common policy for a long time, using an
Enforcer class to replace the old check function. In order to sync the
common policy to ironic, We have to also change the ironic policy and
related unittests.
related change-id:Ife909bdf3277ef33c2fb1eae16ae261fa6374c63
        change-id:Ife84189be4b86a3ee90da4539ff2dbed125be23d

Change-Id: I8618aa1722a313a6a036e68979fb7603def9a292
Closes-Bug: #1288178

@Lucas, 

Thanks for the API changes!

Also, I question whether we need a new config option for this.

Given that the periodic job will, at most, rebuild state for $periodic_max_workers nodes per run, it is misleading to have a config option which suggests it will control how often the sync completes. It, in fact, only controls how often the sync is -checked-, and in larger deployments it will probably take many iterations to complete.

In the ideal case (ring has not changed) this will issue a DB query, walk the results locally, and do nothing more. So I don't think it's necessary to allow it to be tuned by the operator separately from the global default periodic job timing."}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2014-09-29 22:13:07.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2014-09-29 22:56:19.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2014-09-29 23:23:57.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-30 00:22:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified+1

I just got through testing this in a multi-conductor setup. I ran devstack on one node (call this c1, and ran ironic-conductor on a second node (call this c2).

What I did: Run c1, deploy to a node. Spin up c2, spin down c1. c2 successfully took over, wrote images to tftp root, updated neutron, etc. Did a hard power off, power on. Node did *not* come up, did not see a TFTP request on c2. However, neutron was properly configured, so I assumed network issues. I brought up c1, shut down c2. Successful take_over on c1. Power cycled again, node came up properly.

I think we're good here, I saw enough to presume this works as expected.

+1 as I've only skimmed the code, will review tomorrow (it's late)."}, {'account_id': 10239, 'date': '2014-10-02 07:12:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 13:
