If you wanna fully test it we need two conductors on different hosts as Jim said.

To test the cache of the images and generation of the config files it's possible to do in 1 vm:

 - Just run devsstack, deploy a node.

 - cp the /etc/ironic/ironic.conf to a diff place and:
 -- un-comment change the DEFAULT.host option to something else
 -- change the pxe.tftp_root to a diff path
 -- change the pxe.tftp_master_path to a diff path

 - run a new conductor pointing to the new config file

 - kill the old conductor

So you will see the new conductor taking over the node, generating the config files, caching the image and sending a request to update neutron. revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-28 01:46:46.000000000', 'message': "WIP: add periodic task to rebuild hash rings

This adds a periodic task which refreshes the conductor's hash ring.
For any node which is newly mapped to the conductor, this will
trigger calling prepare() and take_over().

This uses the periodic_max_worker setting like other periodic jobs,
starting the take over process in separate threads. Thus, in a large
cluster, it may take some time for all nodes to settle down.

There is a lot of room for improvement and optimization in this, however
getting a fix in place is critical to the Juno release.

Change-Id: I0dbe9a5a98ec5fd0c69f32d7590d8141da5a23c2
Closes-bug: #1279331

"}, {'created': '2014-09-29 22:13:07.000000000', 'message': "Add periodic task to rebuild conductor local state

This adds a periodic task which can rebuild the conductor's local state
(PXE config files, etc) when conductors join or leave the cluster.

For any node which is newly mapped to the conductor, this will
trigger calling prepare() and take_over() on that node's deploy
interface.

This uses the periodic_max_worker setting like other periodic jobs,
starting the take over process in separate threads. Thus, in a large
cluster, it may take some time for all nodes to settle down.

There is a lot of room for improvement and optimization in this, however
getting a fix in place is critical to the Juno release.

Co-Authored-By: Lucas Alvares Gomes <lucasagomes@gmail.com>
Change-Id: I0dbe9a5a98ec5fd0c69f32d7590d8141da5a23c2
Closes-bug: #1279331
"}, {'created': '2014-09-29 22:56:19.000000000', 'message': "Add periodic task to rebuild conductor local state

This adds a periodic task which can rebuild the conductor's local state
(PXE config files, etc) when conductors join or leave the cluster.

For any node which is newly mapped to the conductor, this will
trigger calling prepare() and take_over() on that node's deploy
interface.

This uses the periodic_max_worker setting like other periodic jobs,
starting the take over process in separate threads. Thus, in a large
cluster, it may take some time for all nodes to settle down.
It also adds a new CONF option to control the timing of this job.

There is a lot of room for improvement and optimization in this, however
getting a fix in place is critical to the Juno release.

Co-Authored-By: Lucas Alvares Gomes <lucasagomes@gmail.com>
Change-Id: I0dbe9a5a98ec5fd0c69f32d7590d8141da5a23c2

starting the take over process in separate threads. Thus, in a large
cluster, it may take some time for all nodes to settle down.
It also adds a new CONF option to control the timing of this job.

There is a lot of room for improvement and optimization in this, however
getting a fix in place is critical to the Juno release.

NOTE: This does not re-establish any console sessions.

commit_message:
Add periodic task to rebuild conductor local state

This adds a periodic task which can rebuild the conductor's local state
(PXE config files, etc) when conductors join or leave the cluster.

For any node which is newly mapped to the conductor, this will
trigger calling prepare() and take_over() on that node's deploy
interface.

This uses the periodic_max_worker setting like other periodic jobs,
starting the take over process in separate threads. Thus, in a large
cluster, it may take some time for all nodes to settle down.
It also adds a new CONF option to control the timing of this job.

There is a lot of room for improvement and optimization in this, however
getting a fix in place is critical to the Juno release.

NOTE: This does not re-establish any console sessions.

Co-Authored-By: Lucas Alvares Gomes <lucasagomes@gmail.com>
Change-Id: I0dbe9a5a98ec5fd0c69f32d7590d8141da5a23c2
Closes-bug: #1279331

[{'created': '2014-09-30 15:20:21.000000000', 'message': "Improve share list API filtering

This change adds possibility to filter shares in a lot of possible ways.

All types of share listing were updated to support additional filtering by:
- share network
- snapshot
- volume type
- host
- limit and offset a la pagination
- project id (useful with '--all-tenants')
- metadata (whether specific metadata keys and values are set or not)
- extra-specs (whether any volume type exist and have specific extra-specs
    set up)

And sorting by:
- key of models.Share
- direction (asc, desc)

Implements blueprint improve-share-list-filtering

Change-Id: Ifc53ab27bc710562cc510f30a2c847eda385d5bc

commit_message:
Improve share list API filtering

This change adds possibility to filter shares in a lot of possible ways.

All types of share listing were updated to support additional filtering by:
- share network
- snapshot
- volume type
- host
- limit and offset a la pagination
- project id (useful with '--all-tenants')
- metadata (whether specific metadata keys and values are set or not)
- extra-specs (whether any volume type exists and has specific extra-specs
    set up)

And sorting by:
- key of models.Share
- direction (asc, desc)

Implements blueprint improve-share-list-filtering

Change-Id: Ifc53ab27bc710562cc510f30a2c847eda385d5bc

commit_message:
Handle ambiguous option error for aliases properly

When we have more than one alias for one command option, like
"manila list [--snapshot_id %id%][--snapshot-id %id%]"

We should be ok provided request like following:
"manila list --snapshot %id%"

This change makes above possible.

Also added restriction to use only one alias at a time.

Change-Id: Ibd7de3b75408d50ff97b5b9d19307a5612d7b425
Closes-Bug: #1379472

  image (these should happen in the controller images).

commit_message:
do not perform database or keystone setup in nova-compute

- do not perform database or keystone initialization in nova-compute
  image (these should happen in the controller images).
- fix incorrect nova.conf path
- configure keystone_authtoken correct

NB: This still won't result in a working image, because it does not
configure the RPC settings yet.  That will be for a subsequent patch.

Change-Id: Icbd66104ef817d360c46003b29fff63f66ace8d2

commit_message:
Remove arp notify from delete_port transaction

Move the call to notify L3 agents that arp table entries should be
removed out of the delete_port transaction to eliminate the lock wait
timeouts in the dvr check queue job.

Closes-Bug: #1379148

Co-author: Carl Baldwin <carl.baldwin@hp.com>

Change-Id: If678db2c688a4bbace27006e5ca5f2e6dd6323cf

commit_message:
Add dhcp-sequential-ip option to dnsmasq

For many simultaneously DHCPDISCOVER requests dnsmasq
can offer the same IP for two different MAC addresses.
This option prevents it by assigning IPs one by one
instead of using hashing algorithm.

Change-Id: Iff3c42d21e1f1c09cb9eab5f07dbb066508dcb56
Related-bug: 1378000
Related-bug: 1376680
Related-bug: 1379917
Blueprint: 100-nodes-support

Installation struct API call

* jsonschema and model for InstallationStruct added

commit_message:
Forbid update of HA property of routers

While the HA property is update-able, and resulting router-get
invocations suggest that the router is HA, the migration
itself fails on the agent. This is deceiving and confusing
and should be blocked until the migration itself is fixed
in a future patch.

Change-Id: I4171ab481e3943e0110bd9a300d965bbebe44871
Related-Bug: #1365426
Closes-Bug: #1378525

The PUBLIC_IP variable is not really public

I found that PUBLIC_IP does not result in a public network that k8s
can route.  For example after a boot:
keystone: http://10.251.5.2:5000/v2.0
glance: http://10.251.4.3:9292

'}]
commit_message:
Remove PUBLIC_IP for glance

The PUBLIC_IP variable is not really public

I found that PUBLIC_IP does not result in a public network that k8s
can route.  For example after a boot:
keystone: http://10.251.5.2:5000/v2.0
glance: http://10.251.4.3:9292

these 10.251 networks cannot communicate with one another.  The 10.0.0.z can
communicate just fine, so reverting to that behavior.

Change-Id: I40178e0c0b9778e6158edca76b4256608e2f975e

commit_message:
Remove PUBLIC_IP for keystone

The PUBLIC_IP variable is not really public

I found that PUBLIC_IP does not result in a public network that k8s
can route.  For example after a boot:

keystone: http://10.251.5.2:5000/v2.0
glance: http://10.251.4.3:9292

these 10.251 networks cannot communicate with one another.  The 10.0.0.z can
communicate just fine, so reverting to that behavior.

Change-Id: I07febc0c81149aadbcd6b70704a0873c3c34bb57

commit_message:
Add kube services

Add kubernetes services so that the nova controller
can use the ports 8773, 8774, and 8775, which correspond with
nova-api, nova-ec2-api, and metadata-api.

Change-Id: Idb083e2e0745c6587f9fa4f01a068727a435c2c6

Update nova-controller's container ports

The previous values were just stand in values.  The new
ports support nova-api, ec2 api, and metadata api.

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-14 11:57:14.000000000', 'message': 'Fix recording failure for system pollster

The parameter "cumulative" was interpreted as a list and could
not be recognized as a valid Type for SQL query hence failing
to record the data for the pollster.

The presence of ',' operator in the pollster class after the term
CUMULATIVE caused it to be treated as a list

This is corrected to interpret the field as a string which will
be successfully recorded to the meter database.

Change-Id: I10a69134a7f0c42a3e6c0d9bb7568e8d8fd2a932
Closes-Bug: 1378742
(cherry picked from commit f8f63d4b15ce68797d6e16943bd85efb19a77752)
'}]
commit_message:
Fix recording failure for system pollster

The parameter "cumulative" was interpreted as a list and could
not be recognized as a valid Type for SQL query hence failing
to record the data for the pollster.

The presence of ',' operator in the pollster class after the term
CUMULATIVE caused it to be treated as a list

This is corrected to interpret the field as a string which will
be successfully recorded to the meter database.

Change-Id: I10a69134a7f0c42a3e6c0d9bb7568e8d8fd2a932
Closes-Bug: 1378742
(cherry picked from commit f8f63d4b15ce68797d6e16943bd85efb19a77752)

commit_message:
Remove unused imports from neutron api

This patch removes conductor and security_group module which
are unused any more from neutron api.

Change-Id: I812f3038c5671e7605ebc01bb9cec77304269143

commit_message:
Adds option for excluding files from autodoc trees

The arguments originally being passed into sphinx.apidoc specify '.'
as the path to index. Unfortunately this includes the setup.py module.
This causes Sphinx to complain or break depending on the configuration.

This patch ignores setup.py by default and allows the project to
override it in their setup.cfg.

Change-Id: I7c164d42a096ba1a0daf314a689cc3252ca81c49
Closes-Bug: #1260495

commit_message:
Fix next on SourceFile

next(iterable) is supposed to return the next thing in the sequence;
here, that's a bunch of zeros. However, this was returning a generator
that yielded one item: a bunch of zeros. This broke direct
benchmarking.

Change-Id: I2fca4795fc9b3d1637c72616a52a60482d6e853e

commit_message:
Increase verbosity of Firewall check results

Create dump of iptables rules before running check
and increase verbosity of log message if test fails.
Also do not remove temporary check file, just rename it.

Change-Id: I55fa25e7ef0d2a42899b98600297741ad53d931c
Closes-bug: #1378745

are already managing everything with default OS
providers. Moreover, this commit is error-prone

commit_message:
Do not kill swift replicator services

To move from exec to SysV provider of the service
in previous releases we had to kill swift replicator
service with swift-init kill command.

This is not what we need in 6.0 release as we
are already managing everything with default OS
providers. Moreover, this commit is error-prone
for Ubuntu with upstart provider.

Change-Id: I9ed3a030b4987f919a9f9ec2d9351f0b2c3623b0
Closes-bug: #1381018

commit_message:
Update child_members to use a Set

Updates the impl_ifcfg.child_members method so that it
uses a set instead of an array (this avoids dups). Also
fixes an issue with this method which would cause tests
to fail intermittently due to ordering differences.
Adding each member object regardless solves this
(not sure why I had commented out the children.append before)

Also fixes an issue in test_cli which causes tests to fail
on Debian which doesn't yet support the add_bond method
on its ENI provider. This fix was to explicitly set
--provider=ifcfg on the failing tests. We should be able to
remove these once ENI supports bonding properly.

Closes-bug: #1370615

Change-Id: Id9cfa2b2eaab27c93113956f5956facfa2a2aeee

In addition to echoing steve's comments (don't hardcode ips), nova.conf has some really weird backslashing going on. I don't think it will do what you think it will do.

For a line that looks like:

  crudini --set /etc/nova/nova.conf\ DEFAULT\ amqp_durable_queues\ False

That should be either:

  crudini --set /etc/nova/nova.conf DEFAULT amqp_durable_queues False


Or:

  crudini --set /etc/nova/nova.conf\
    DEFAULT\
    amqp_durable_queues\
    False"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-14 01:50:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

commit_message:
Add config setup, api services, and controller servies

The nova-controller will serve as the 'base' image and populate
the nova.conf file on start.  The configurations will be pulled
from 'nova.conf'.

Adding kubernetes setup for the api and controller.

Change-Id: I29bdc96bee4a6a5a301438383d308f402c9432e0

commit_message:
Correct response status for HEAD requests

The response status for some HEAD calls was changed to follow the
HTTP specification a while back.  Specifically, any call that supports
both GET and HEAD methods should return the same response code.  The
API docs still list all successfull HEAD requests with a response code
of 204, which is not correct in all cases.

This patch adjusts the expected response status for HEAD calls to
match the actual implementation.

Change-Id: I6f518ebbe00a0b2860ca5db0d10b93f313abd488
Related-bug: #1334368

[{'created': '2014-09-28 20:11:21.000000000', 'message': 'Added symlink/dereference and modified lvm auto guess options

The following options are added/modified:
- --dereference-symlink: Follow Hard and soft links and archive
  and dump the files they refer to.
- --lvm-auto-snap: now takes as argument the path you want to
  guess for the lvm group and volume name

Also few types where removed. Dependencies are also update,
as now pymongo and mysqldb module needs to be installed

Change-Id: I99b780ff7b34dd85162634855357e1785db0e893
'}, {'created': '2014-10-13 09:33:26.000000000', 'message': "Added symlink/dereference and modified lvm auto guess options

The following options are added/modified:
- --dereference-symlinki {'none', 'soft', 'hard', 'all'}:
    Follow Hard and soft links and archive and dump the files
    they refer to according the choise option set.
- --lvm-auto-snap: now takes as argument the path you want to
  guess for the lvm group and volume name

Also few types where removed. Dependencies are also update,

commit_message:
Added symlink/dereference and modified lvm auto guess options

The following options are added/modified:
- --dereference-symlink {'none', 'soft', 'hard', 'all'}:
    Follow Hard and soft links and archive and dump the files
    they refer to according the choise option set.
- --lvm-auto-snap: now takes as argument the path you want to
  guess for the lvm group and volume name

Also few types where removed. Dependencies are also update,
as now pymongo and mysqldb module needs to be installed

Change-Id: I99b780ff7b34dd85162634855357e1785db0e893

commit_message:
Add instance number as weight for scheduler

Add instance number as weight for scheduler, so in some cases the
scheduler will select a better host to spawn on it.

Change-Id: I7879f4eb00485054a27915a496b521da2bc35d6e

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Gerrit_Workflow
    Commit Messages: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages"}, {'account_id': 6659, 'date': '2014-10-10 17:37:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

commit_message:
Update VPN logging to use new i18n functions

For log messages in neutron/services/vpn and neutron/db/vpn, replace
_() marker functions with log-level-specific marker functions: _LI(),
_LW(), _LE() from oslo.i18n.

Also, remove _() functions for debug log messages as debug level log
messages should not be translated.

Change-Id: I07fcf25bb6344c47e74d6ee23f9bc08e4b560679
Closes-Bug: #1379811

commit_message:
Add dox file to test with container

Dox is a tool to run tests (like tox) but with containers. You will need
to install it directly from the git repo to test it :

https://github.com/stackforge/dox

and just run the command dox which should launch the docker container to
test the puppet module.

The image currently used is one generated by myself, in the future this
would be moved to the infra namespace properly (where we hope to
centralise infra docker images).

Change-Id: I3e0e72ea020157a84caf3c67269d844aa5b45de9

batch operations in nova-compute dockerfile

- batch yum operations to the build goes faster
- yum clean after install to remove yum cache and make
  final image smaller

Add Check to see if congress has started in devstack

This will be useful once our CI is running so we can fail early if
congress failed to start.

commit_message:
Configure logging for keepalived

Redirect keepalived logs to /var/log/keepalived/keepalived.log and
allow configurable dump_conf and log_detail to increase logging

Change-Id: I8afbcf883d8a95a7a1fb8fd3bda67a00c801a899

commit_message:
Add time-sync functionality to dos.py

Add functionality to sync time on
specific env nodes on demand using dos.py

Related-Bug: #1318641

Change-Id: If26abc316a80e31fb575fec0ebffa1685025d556

commit_message:
SELinux: swift denied access to /var/lib/swift/.local

Swift services cannot search /var/lib/swift/.local. This is a
custom policy to allow search for swift until the upstream SELinux
policy is updated.

Change-Id: Ie6197cc63597e29f0e84f97d67b1935c67e54a53
Partial-Bug: 1379081

commit_message:
Set permissions on nailgun files installed

Includes a workaround in nginx start.sh script to
reset permissions on /usr/share/nailgun/static
because Docker resets it to 700.

Change-Id: I9172a888cd72ded9ce16897b1e779d994b9802e7
Closes-Bug: #1380950

commit_message:
Add lock status into output of instance detail

Currently we only support locking/unlocking an instance but we are not able
to query whether the instance is locked or not.
This proposal is to add the lock status to the detailed view of an instance.

blue print link:
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/nova/+spec/get-lock-status-of-instance

Change-Id: I32545e27f7b3657fad858dc3e056d64f39cae1d5

commit_message:
VMWare: Fix VM leak when deletion of VM during resizing

During the VM resizing, before VM arrive RESIZED state, driver
migrate_disk_and_power_off will initially rename orginal vm
'uuid' to be 'uuid-orig' and clone a new vm with 'uuid' name.
When deletion VM is triggered at this time window, it wouldn't
be able to delete the VM uuid-orig in VCenter and so cause VM leak.
As VM task state will be set to 'deleting' and it can not be used to
determine the resize migrating/migrated state, this fix will
attempt to delete orig VM within destroy phase.

Conflicts:
	nova/tests/virt/vmwareapi/test_driver_api.py
	nova/virt/vmwareapi/vmops.py

Closes-Bug: #1359138

NOTE: the aformentioned patch broke Minesweeper. The fix was also
cherry picked from commit e464bc518e8590d59c2741948466777982ca3319.
This was to do two things:
1. Solve the actual bug
2. Ensure that the unit tests and Minesweeper passed

Change-Id: I7598afbf0dc3c527471af34224003d28e64daaff
(cherry-picked from e1f8664c9fa83f77f5bb763ffcc3157905ed954c)

(2 comments)

Paul, I'm wondering what the purpose of storing this information in the database is if it is essentially static information that can be queried from the dom0 itself? For instance, why can't the resource tracker (or the scheduler for that matter) ask the compute node for this information on some (very long) periodic interval? AFAICT, it's similar data to the CPU spec information we grab on a periodic basis from the hypervisor, which is also something I don't believe makes sense to be in the database, since it's essentially static information and we don't perform queries on it.

Do you have a description of a use case that this supported_instances field is supposed to be fulfilling?

Thanks!

-jay"}, {'account_id': 7461, 'date': '2014-10-01 07:08:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi Jay,

The supported_instances field is an existing field in the compute_nodes table. It is currently provided by all the hypervisors and used in the scheduler image_props_filter.

It is missing from the ComputeNode object, so this patch is adding it so we can complete the objects work.

I will amend the commit message to make all the above clear. I didn't mean to give the impression that this was a new addition. Sorry if that's how it came across."}, {'account_id': 7461, 'date': '2014-10-01 08:02:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Jay, to answer your question more directly, you are probably right. The use case is to do with selecting hosts in mixed hypervisor/architecture environments. The information is compared to architecture, hypervisor type and virtualisation mode if set in the request spec. I suppose in theory the hypervisor running on a host can change, but as you say, it is likely to be long term.

However, this patch is about conversion to objects, so this discussion probably belongs elsewhere. But worth thinking about.'}, {'account_id': 7166, 'date': '2014-10-01 09:18:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

commit_message:
Add supported_hv_specs to ComputeNode object

The compute_nodes table has a field called supported_instances
that is populated with data generated by the virt drivers
and used in the scheduler filter image_props_filter. There is
no corresponding field in the ComputeNode object. This change
adds a field called supported_hv_specs that maps to the
supported_instances database field.

The field is a list of specs for hypervisor properties
(architecture, hypervisor type and vm mode) that the host supports.
The change of name to supported_hv_specs is intended to reflect
this and is made now as a change in the object later on would
require a change in the object version.

Because the field has a defined structure a field type is defined
for supported_hv_specs. The field type is:

    ListOfObjectsField('HVSpec')

where HVSpec is a new object representing the a supported
hypervisor property combination.

Change-Id: I8b41465c4f3b391be38e16260a807d9d3fe60ec2

commit_message:
Sync with latest oslo-incubator

Changes include:
55ca7c3 Split cliutils
1b44601 Allow dictionary lookup in credentials with dot notation
6c706c5 Delete graduated serialization files
3edbfb3 remove caching param from prettytable call
9ce1d96 Fix i18n import
5d40e14 Remove code that moved to oslo.i18n
a4be4ed Remove graduated config modules
6ff6b4b Switch oslo-incubator to use oslo.utils and remove old modules
70189c9 Remove graduated test and fixtures libraries
8b71f57 Delete graduated db files
6ede600 rpc, notifier: remove deprecated modules
6b65a41 Fix build break - switch from str to hash for lookup
f76f44c Delete the token and endpoint on expiry of token of client
aebb58f Fix typo to show correct log message
1131b56 Enabled mask_password to handle byte code strings
6b048e7 Let oslotest manage the six.move setting for mox

Change-Id: Ic588aec0fc0291440feaac3439836054bd3608cd

It's fine but I would recommend to increase this number rather than remove.
For example in ten times: sed -i "s/1024/10240/g" /etc/security/limits.d/90-nproc.conf

Short description of this constraint: 
# Default limit for number of user's processes to prevent 
# accidental fork bombs.'}, {'account_id': 13343, 'date': '2014-10-07 14:41:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 8787, 'date': '2014-10-07 21:31:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

No, removing it is not fine since it exposes the system to forkbomb DoS attacks. It should instead be increased as suggested by Stanislav.'}, {'account_id': 8787, 'date': '2014-10-07 21:36:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Also, commit should have Partial-Bug: 1331554 instead of Closes-Bug: 1376564.'}, {'account_id': 11827, 'date': '2014-10-08 08:08:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: -Code-Review

Dmitry Borodaenko, what's wrong with editing /etc/security/limits.conf instead /etc/security/limits.d/*?"}, {'account_id': 13344, 'date': '2014-10-08 09:16:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Stas and Dmitry, I suggest to add this to puppet in limits.conf if needed. Anyway the maximum will be different for different cases.'}, {'account_id': 8787, 'date': '2014-10-08 20:04:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

The problem with single limits.conf is that you will not be able to manage different lines in that file from different Puppet resources. Even if you use concat, it will still all tie into a single resource that is created all at once. Why create yourself a problem in the future if you already have a separate file for this specific parameter that you can populate with the right lines?

As to "when needed", it is needed right now. As I pointed out in my original comment, it's not ok to simply remove a security restriction and hope that we will not forget to add it back in the future.

Also please comment on what are your thoughts on #1331554 (I've marked #1376564 as a duplicate of that)? Do you plan to expand this commit to address the rest of the problems with limits (see comments from Christopher), or only fix nproc for CentOS here? I can see a point in the second option as long as this by itself would be enough to downgrade #1331554 from High to Medium.'}, {'account_id': 11827, 'date': '2014-10-09 08:21:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

Ok.
If speak about how puppet works with resources then - yes, will better to save 90-nproc.conf due to convinience.'}, {'account_id': 13344, 'date': '2014-10-09 09:30:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Then, if we are going to keep that file, what will be the maximum?'}, {'account_id': 8787, 'date': '2014-10-09 19:18:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

10240 (10K, current limit multiplied by 10) should be enough.'}, {'account_id': 13344, 'date': '2014-10-10 10:07:47.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-10 10:07:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

commit_message:
Increases the number of processes in CentOS 6.X

Increases the number of processes per user in /etc/security/limits.d/90-nproc.conf
for CentOS 6.X due to bug https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=919793

Change-Id: I76f258f33325f80fe06167dec08d81dabd292163
Closes-Bug: 1376564

commit_message:
Add monit as an option for compute nodes

* Add use_monit (Default false) for site.pp
  If enabled, will install and configure monit watchdogs for
  specified services and roles (compute & cinder).
* Changes to cluster_ha.pp/cluster_simple.pp:
  - Add monit watchdogs for nova-compute/network/api for compute
    nodes by mathcing the python processes.
  - Add monit watchdogs for cinder-volume for cinder nodes
    by mathcing the python processes
  - Add monit watchdog for ovs service by its pid for computes.

DocImpact
Related blueprint pacemaker-improvements

Change-Id: Ia622d3200db1b78a0cf4e6b1da1ceff0604e8a16
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Adapt monit module for Fuel needs

* Lower service health polling from 120 to 30 sec
* Add timeout for start/stop actions
* Add pidless services tracking as well (e.g. we will
  need it for nova-compute, nova-network)
* Add params for Redhat/Centos support
* Make config template params based
* Add syslog support
* Redefine service's provider to monit, if already
  in catalog
* Adjust rspecs
* Add docs

Related blueprint pacemaker-improvements

Change-Id: Id4f594ceda640175f20594c6a4787c8c0145f433
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-10-02 06:59:13.000000000', 'message': "Add a job for functional tests in zaqarclient

We'd like to test every patch submitted for zaqarclient against a live
running zaqar server. This patch adds a new zaqarclient job that
installs zaqar and runs the client functional tests.

This job has, temporarily, been made non-voting until we're sure it
works as expected. This is a prevention to avoid blocking the client
patches on a broken job. Once it works as expected, I'll add the job to
the gate pipeline and make it voting.

Change-Id: Ia5b47bfc02b2c53ccbc2a73729961a9d5fdd9b6d
"}, {'created': '2014-10-03 06:36:34.000000000', 'message': "Add a job for functional tests in zaqarclient

We'd like to test every patch submitted for zaqarclient against a live
running zaqar server. This patch adds a new zaqarclient job that
installs zaqar and runs the client functional tests.

This job has, temporarily, been made non-voting until we're sure it
works as expected. This is a prevention to avoid blocking the client

commit_message:
Add a job for functional tests in zaqarclient

We'd like to test every patch submitted for zaqarclient against a live
running zaqar server. This patch adds a new zaqarclient job that
installs zaqar and runs the client functional tests.

This job has, temporarily, been made non-voting until we're sure it
works as expected. This is a prevention to avoid blocking the client
patches on a broken job. Once it works as expected, I'll add the job to
the gate pipeline and make it voting.

Change-Id: Ia5b47bfc02b2c53ccbc2a73729961a9d5fdd9b6d
